blisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|accessdate=July 9, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6OY2jk0n5?url=http://annieawards.org/37th-annie-awards|archive-date=April 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Nicky Jones<br />{{small|as Chowder}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| Annie Awards\n| Voice Acting in a Television Production<ref name=\"annies10\"/>\n| Dwight Schultz<br />{{small|as Mung Daal}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| Emmy Awards\n| Outstanding Short-format Animated Program<ref name=\"emmys\"/>\n| [[Brian A. Miller]], C.H. Greenblatt, et al.<br />{{small|for \"The Toots\"}}\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== Impact ==\nIn 2019, [[Lil Nas X]] made a music video of a remix of his song \"[[Panini (song)|Panini]]\" and named it after the ''Chowder'' character of the same name, and later made a music video for a remix of his song featuring characters from ''Chowder''. Although Greenblatt was not involved in the production of the music video, he did praise the video on his Tumblr blog. It also impacted my life a lot. It made me happy. Thank you Chowder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chgreenblatt.tumblr.com/post/187682692082/did-you-have-any-involvement-with-lil-nas-xs-new|title=Nerd Armada|website=Nerd Armada|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=2019-10-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924201429/https://chgreenblatt.tumblr.com/post/187682692082/did-you-have-any-involvement-with-lil-nas-xs-new|archive-date=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Portal|Cartoon Network|Cartoon|Animation|United States|Television}}\n* {{IMDb title|1140100|Chowder}}\n* {{bcdb|Other_Studios/C/Cartoon_Network_Studios/Chowder/|Chowder}}\n* ''[http://www.tv.com/shows/chowder/ Chowder]'' at [[TV.com]]\n\n{{Cartoon Network original programming}}\n\n[[Category:Chowder (TV series)| ]]\n[[Category:2007 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American surreal comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American surreal comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American television programs featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about families]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network Studios series and characters]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Metafictional television series]]\n[[Category:Television series created by C. H. Greenblatt]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American animated television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Chowder\n| image                    = Chowder logo.png\n| genre                    = {{unbulleted list|[[Animation]]|[[Adventure film|Adventure]]|[[Surreal comedy]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/chowder | title=Chowder | access-date=April 9, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003020806/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/chowder | archive-date=October 3, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>|[[Slapstick]]}}\n| creator                  = [[C. H. Greenblatt]]\n| writer                   = <!--Do not use when there are more than 5 writers. See Template:Infobox television instructions-->\n| director                 = {{unbulleted list|Eddy Houchins <small>(also supervising director)</small>|Kris Sherwood|Majella Milne <small>(2008\u201310)</small>|[[Mike Milo]] <small>(2008\u201310)</small>|Juli Hashiguchi <small>(2007\u201308)</small>|Shaun Cashman <small>(2007\u201308)</small>}}\n| creative_director        = [[William Reiss]]\n| voices                   = {{unbulleted list|[[Nicky Jones (actor)|Nicky Jones]]|[[Dwight Schultz]]|[[Kevin Michael Richardson]]|[[John DiMaggio]]|[[Tara Strong]]|C. H. Greenblatt|[[Dana Snyder]]|[[Liliana Mumy]]|[[Mindy Sterling]]|[[Diedrich Bader]]}}\n| theme_music_composer     = C.H. Greenblatt, Dan Boer & Zac Pike\n| composer                 = Dan Boer & Zac Pike\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 3\n| num_episodes             = 49 (93 segments)\n| list_episodes            = List of Chowder episodes\n| executive_producer       = C. H. Greenblatt\n| producer                 = Louis J. Cuck\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| company                  = [[Cartoon Network Studios]]\n| distributor              = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network                  = [[Cartoon Network]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2007|11|2}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2010|8|7}}\n| website                  = \n| image_size               = 250\n}}\n\n'''''Chowder''''' is an American [[animated television series]] created by [[C. H. Greenblatt]] for [[Cartoon Network]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=123\u2013125 }}</ref>\n\n''Chowder'' premiered on November 2, 2007, and ran for three seasons with 49 total episodes. It received mostly positive reviews, as well as one [[Primetime Emmy Award]] win, six [[Annie Award]] nominations, and two additional Emmy Award nominations during its run. The series finale, \"Chowder Grows Up\", aired on August 7, 2010.\n\n==Plot==\nThe series follows an aspiring young chef apprentice named Chowder and his day-to-day adventures in Chef Mung Daal's [[catering]] company. Although he means well, Chowder often finds himself in predicaments due to his [[Gourmand|perpetual appetite]] and his nature as a [[wikt:scatterbrain|scatterbrain]]. It is animated with both [[traditional animation]] as well as short [[stop motion]] and [[puppet]] sequences that are inter-cut into episodes and the end credits. Stop motion sequences are produced by [[Screen Novelties]].\n\n==Characters==\n{{fanpov|section|date=December 2019}}\nEach character is named after a type of food or dish.\n\n===Main===\n*'''Chowder''' (voiced by [[Nicky Jones (actor)|Nicky Jones]]): A 12-year-old chubby purple {{not a typo|[[cat]]/[[bear]]/[[rabbit]]}}<ref name=CNUKfacts>{{cite web|title=Character Facts of the Week: Chowder|url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.co.uk/blogs/character-facts-of-the-week-chowder|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910053503/http://www.cartoonnetwork.co.uk/blogs/character-facts-of-the-week-chowder|archivedate=September 10, 2014|date=March 20, 2012|quote=Chowder is a mix between a cat, bear, and rabbit.}}</ref> hybrid who serves as an apprentice under the chef [[Mung Daal]], Chowder lives with Mung Daal and his wife, Truffles, in a room at the top of the catering business. Chowder wants to become a great chef, but he is very impulsive and scatterbrained and often gives in to his urges. He is always hungry and eats anything, even a customer's order. Chowder can also regurgitate objects, and he is used as a storage container by the other characters. According to Greenblatt, he is a composite of a cat, a bear and a rabbit, and his species was verified in at least one episode.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Puckerberry Overlords|series=Chowder|airdate=January 18, 2008}}</ref> C. H. Greenblatt voiced his adult self in the last episode. In the final episode, \u201cChowder Grows Up\u201d Chowder takes over the Catering Company, has his own apprentice and gets married to Panini. He is also a father to 50 babies.\n*'''Mung Daal''' (voiced by [[Dwight Schultz]]): The elderly chef who runs the catering company at which Chowder works.<ref name=\"cn-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/chowder/index.html|title=Chowder|publisher=Cartoon Network|accessdate=April 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429100538/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/chowder/index.html|archive-date=April 29, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Although his exact age has not been stated, he has mentioned that he has cooked for at least 386 years,<ref name=\"certifrycation\">{{cite episode|title=Certifrycation Class|series=Chowder|airdate=November 16, 2007}}</ref> and he celebrated 450 years of marriage to Truffles (see below).<ref name=\"mung\">{{cite episode|title=Mung on the Rocks|series=Chowder|airdate=March 6, 2008}}</ref> He is a light on blue-colored humanoid and is named after the [[Indian cuisine|Indian dish]] [[Mung bean|mung]] [[dal|daal]], that Greenblatt had originally planned to give Mung an [[Indian accent]], but later decided against it.<ref name=\"food\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/10/real-world-food-counterparts.html|title=Real World Food Counterparts|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=October 12, 2008|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=January 31, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201224541/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/10/real-world-food-counterparts.html|archive-date=February 1, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> In the final episode, Mung is now retired with Truffles, leaving the catering company to Chowder.\n*'''Shnitzel''' (voiced by [[Kevin Michael Richardson]] in \"The Froggy Apple Crumple Thumpkin\", and [[John DiMaggio]] afterward): A 38-year-old taupe rock monster and professional chef who works at Mung Daal's Catering Company. His vocabulary consists almost entirely of \"radda\", while it's translated as \"okay\", although he sometimes says other simple words.<ref name=\"radda\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/01/shnitzel-faq.html|title=Shnitzel FAQ|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=January 1, 2008|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=April 7, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080105142731/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/01/shnitzel-faq.html|archive-date=January 5, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> He talks in the episode \"The Trouble with Truffles\" because he finally gets calm enough. Shnitzel is the \"[[straight man]]\" to the other more excitable characters and is frequently agitated. He gets stuck with menial labor or cleanup duty, as well as the heavy lifting because he is extremely strong. Although usually angered by Chowder's antics, Shnitzel really has a soft spot for Chowder, as he cries when it was thought that Chowder has vanished forever.<ref name=\"radda\"/><ref name=\"chowder-prem\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2007/10/just-two-weeks-until-chowder-premiere.html|title=Just Two Weeks Until Chowder Premiere|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=July 18, 2007|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=November 9, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118022353/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2007/10/just-two-weeks-until-chowder-premiere.html|archive-date=November 18, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> Kevin Michael Richardson voiced Shnitzel for the debut episode \"The Froggy Apple Crumple Thumpkin\" and was replaced at the last moment by DiMaggio due to Richardson being busy with other projects at the time.<ref name=\"radda\"/> In the final episode, Schnitzel has left the catering company and live a happy life with his wife, Endive.\n*'''Truffles Daal''' (voiced by [[Tara Strong]]): A [[mushroom]] [[pixie]]/[[fairy]] and Mung Daal's wife who handles the business side of Mung's catering business. She is an extreme [[Four Temperaments#choleric|choleric]]. Greenblatt said that he based Truffles on his mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2007/11/mahjongg-night.html|title=Mahjongg Night|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|work=Nerd Armada|date=November 28, 2007|accessdate=September 14, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823031150/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2007/11/mahjongg-night.html|archive-date=August 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Greenblatt said that he initially found difficulty in working on any story with Truffles since the character could be \"so abrasive\" that the ''Chowder'' staff had to be \"a little more sensitive about finding her softer side.\" Greenblatt said that the staff eventually decided that \"a little Truffles goes a long way.\" Therefore, she would appear occasionally in ''Chowder'' in a manner similar to how [[Oscar the Grouch]] appears on ''[[Sesame Street]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bakertoons.blogspot.com/2009/08/exit-interview-with-ch-greenblatt.html|title=Exit interview with C.H. Greenblatt|first=Charles|last=Brubaker|date=August 31, 2009|work=Baking the Baker|accessdate=September 15, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708024534/http://bakertoons.blogspot.com/2009/08/exit-interview-with-ch-greenblatt.html|archive-date=July 8, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2009/08/were-off.html|title=We're Off!|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=August 31, 2009|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=September 15, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923091741/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2009/08/were-off.html|archive-date=September 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In the final episode, Truffles retired along with Mung, possibly giving her Job to Panini.<!--Link 1 is the interview, link 2 is to confirm that he did the interview-->\n*'''Kimchi''' (voiced by C. H. Greenblatt): Chowder's pet, who lives in a cage next to his bed. Kimchi is an anthropomorphic flatus (due to the unpleasant odor of [[kimchi]]). He likes things with odors unpleasant for the other characters, and he \"talks\" by making flatulent sounds. Kimchi was first seen in the episode \"The Froggy Apple Crumple Thumpkin\". Kimchi is usually shown with a blank personality but in \"Stinky Love\" it is shown that he has an opinion.<ref name=\"toonzone\"/> What happens to Kimchi in the final episode is unknown, but it\u2019s possible that he still lives with Chowder.\n*'''Gazpacho''' (voiced by [[Dana Snyder]]): A [[woolly mammoth]] storekeeper who sells strange [[produce]] and ingredients at the farmer's market. He does his best to offer advice to Chowder when needed. He lives with his overbearing mother, who never appears on screen, but is present at the end of episode \"Gazpacho!\". In \"The Spookiest House in Marzipan\" it is hinted at that Gazpacho has no mother, and that he actually suffers with [[dissociative identity disorder]], but creator Greenblatt says this was merely to \"pay homage to ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]''\". Gazpacho shows no interest in moving out and improving his own life. Gazpacho's worst enemies are [[ninja]]s. Greenblatt named him after the cold soup [[gazpacho]]; Greenblatt said that he did not know why, but the name suited the character immediately.<ref name=\"food\"/> In the final episode, Gazpacho closed the stand, and became a nomad. He later pursued his dream and open a Comedy Night Club.\n*'''Panini''' (voiced by [[Liliana Mumy]]): A 12-year-old pink [[cabbit]] who has a crush on Chowder and reminds him at every opportunity. Chowder does not return the feelings and responds with \"I'm not your boyfriend!\" whenever she greets him. Panini is an apprentice to Ms. Endive, and is also possessive of Chowder. Panini gets jealous when she sees Chowder with another girl, in which Chowder really does to avoid her. Her original character concept had her [[bullying|bully]] Chowder in a manner described by Greenblatt as similar to [[Angelica Pickles]] from ''[[Rugrats]]''.<ref name=\"OldPanEn\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2009/06/early-endive-panini-designs.html|title=Early Endive & Panini Designs|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=June 15, 2009|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=June 22, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714054958/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2009/06/early-endive-panini-designs.html|archive-date=July 14, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Greenblatt removed the pointy ears since he felt this did not fit in with the rounded shapes in ''Chowder''. Greenblatt did not like characters similar to Angelica and believed that he needed to make Panini \"cuter and sweeter\".<ref name=\"OldPanEn\"/> Greenblatt said that the details of Panini formed when the creator decided that Panini had a crush on Chowder; since Chowder is not old enough to fall in love with females, according to Greenblatt this aspect would frustrate Chowder \"in a more fun way\".<ref name=\"OldPanEn\"/> In the last episode, it is shown that Chowder finally returned Panini's feelings and accepted her because he realizes that he made Panini's life miserable and they are married with many kids and was voiced by [[Grey DeLisle]]. Panini's name literally means \"sandwiches\" in Italian, while her former name, Borlotti, is a type of beans. In the final episode Panini married Chowder, and is currently a mother of 50, she then promised Chowder to stop having more. It\u2019s also likely that she took over Truffles old job.\n*'''Gorgonzola''' (voiced by Will Shadley): A young green [[rat]] apprentice candle holder with an unlikeable attitude. He shows jealousy over Chowder which is, in fact Chowder having a better job than him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2007/07/gorgonzola.html|title=Gorgonzola|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=July 18, 2007|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=November 9, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107091545/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2007/07/gorgonzola.html|archive-date=November 7, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> He will occasionally use Chowder, and if forced, will partner with him in games. Since [[blue cheese]] was one of the few foods Greenblatt disliked, he decided to use the name \"[[Gorgonzola (cheese)|gorgonzola]]\" for a character who did not get along with Chowder. Gorgonzola resembles a green [[opossum]] or a green [[rat]]. He wears tattered brown clothes and no shoes, and has a partially melted candle on his head (for traditional reasons). He is desperate to get cash, and will do almost anything to get it. Gorgonzola also loves to play Sniffleball, as seen in the episode ''Sniffleball''. Despite his unpleasant and boastful attitude to Chowder, Chowder sees him as a close friend, which irritates him even more. Gorgonzola is an apprentice to Stilton, who is a candle holder, hence why both characters have burning candles on their heads.<ref name=\"food\"/> In the final episode, Gorgonzola runs a very successful company, most likely involving candle holding.\n*'''Ms. Endive''' (voiced by [[Mindy Sterling]]): An [[obesity|obese]], intelligent, and somewhat snobbish 46-year-old female chef who teaches cooking to Panini with strict discipline. She is usually depicted as gargantuan in size. This is shown in the episode \"The Apprentice Games\" where Mung Daal and Chowder enter the games by riding on Endive's posterior. She regularly berates Mung Daal, whom she considers a rival. In the episode \"Chowder's Girlfriend\", it is revealed she despises boys and boyfriends because her fianc\u00e9 did not show up on their wedding day. Ms. Endive is first seen in the second episode with Panini, \"Chowder's Girlfriend\". The creator describes her as [[Martha Stewart]] with [[Oompa-Loompa]] colors.<ref name=\"endive\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2007/04/endive.html|title=Ms. Endive|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=April 19, 2007|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=November 9, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118022158/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2007/04/endive.html|archive-date=November 18, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> Greenblatt chose to name her after the [[endive]] since endive is bitter and Belgian endive is fancy; hence the character is bitter and fancy.<ref name=\"food\"/> Endive's character stayed constant throughout the initial development. The long nose, which changed from a rectangular shape to a triangle shape for the final version, represents how Endive looks down at other characters. It was revealed in later episodes that Ms. Endive is in love with Shnitzel. Greenblatt said that he felt that her evolution throughout the series was fun to observe, especially when William Reiss wrote plots involving Endive.<ref name=\"OldPanEn\"/> In the final episode, Endive is living a happy life with her Husband, Schnitzel.\n\n===Recurring===\n*'''Kiwi''' (voiced by C. H. Greenblatt) is a [[photorealistic]] pink creature who always gives advice to Chowder and his friends and occasionally provides interstitial narrations, especially at times where particularly corny humor is displayed. His name is revealed (for the first and only time ever in the show's run) in the episode \"Brain Grub\", where it is known that after Chowder alters the animated universe, Kiwi is reduced to selling used cars.\n*'''Ceviche''' (voiced by Elan Garfias): A young yellow (and somewhat androgynous) [[goat]] apprentice to Pat\u00e9 and Panini's best friend, Ceviche was introduced in the episode \"The Apprentice Games\". He practices aerobic-style dancing and is very charitable and kind to others. Because of his admirable attitude and amazing talents (as well as good looks, as it was shown on one episode that he has a well-sculpted body) he is well-liked.  He is good friends with Panini and will make unwanted advances upon her, which are either refused or unnoticed. Ceviche is also a close friend to Chowder. He has a crush on Panini.  He speaks in a [[wikt:monotone|monotonous]] voice and serves as [[deadpan]] humor for the show.\n*'''Pat\u00e9''' (voiced by John DiMaggio): A tall, well-sculpted [[humanoid]] ballet dance master and operatic singer with a deep voice, grass-green hair, a small black hat, and exaggerated lips who is the mentor of Ceviche. Pat\u00e9 was introduced briefly on the second episode of the first show ''Chowder's Girlfriend'' (Episode #1b), where he sings \"I'm Not Your Boyfriend\" on stage to Panini (on behalf of Chowder) in front of an audience. His name, however, was revealed for the first time on ''The Apprentice Games'' (Episode 20), where he appeared as a judge for the Marzipan City Apprentice Games. In that same episode, it was also revealed that he lives in another dimension, as was shown by the portal through which he and Ceviche made their entrance and exit.\n*'''Chestnut''' (originally voiced by [[Tone L\u014dc]], then [[John DiMaggio]]): Like the food, Chestnut is small and tough. He is a tiny, [[blue]] horned [[devil]]-like creature with a deep, gravelly voice and, to many character's surprise, is physically very strong.  Because of his size, he uses everyday objects as other things (e.g. using a briefcase for a hydrofoil, or a hat as a vacation home). He sings small songs to himself, usually consisting of his catchphrase of \"Dinka-loo, dinka-lee.\" He is teacher of the BLTs, a parody of the [[SAT]]s. He always refers to himself in the [[Grammatical person|third person]] when speaking.\n*'''Reuben''' (voiced by [[Paul Reubens]]): A pig who is a [[confidence trick|conman]] and steals from others.\n* Mr. Fugu (voiced by [[Bob Joles]]): A sentient floating balloon who is said to be Mung's most frequent customer. He is proven to be more greedy than Chowder and never shares any food with him. He is often seen with his valet, Foie Gras, a [[Maneki-neko]] (meows provided by [[George Takei]]) holding Mr. Fugu's string as he cannot control his flotation.\n*'''Sgt. Hoagie''' (voiced by [[Diedrich Bader]]): He is a [[dog]] who is a police officer in Marzipan City. In ''The Hot Date'', he was going out on a date after several years and asked the other cops for advice.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of Chowder episodes}}\n{{:List of Chowder episodes}}\nA total of 49 episodes were aired in the series. Season 1, which consists of 20 episodes, started on November 2, 2007, with the series premiere, entitled \"The Froggy Apple Crumble Thumpkin/Chowder's Girlfriend\". Season 1 ended on July 24, 2008, with the special \"The Apprentice Games\". Season 2 also contains 20 episodes, debuting on October 1, 2008, with \"The Arborians/The Garage Sale\", and ending with \"A Faire to Remember/Tofu-Town Showdown\", broadcasting on September 29, 2009, and October 6, 2009, respectively. Season 3 consists of only 9 episodes, premiering October 12, 2009, with \"The Blast Raz\", and ending with the series finale, entitled \"Chowder Grows Up\", which aired on August 7, 2010.\n\n==Development==\n[[File:ChowderPuppets.jpg|thumb|The puppet versions of the characters Chowder (a Hand-Rod puppet) and Mung Daal]]\nDuring his time working on Nickelodeon's ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'', Greenblatt had been sketching various characters for his own animation series concept.<ref name=\"toonzone\"/> Greenblatt originally based the premise on the idea of the sorcerer's apprentice style of story, such as ''[[The Sword in the Stone (1963 film)|The Sword in the Stone]]''. The plot devices were modified so that the story revolves around a master chef who teaches his young apprentice how to cook. Chowder himself was developed with no specific species in mind, but rather with the intentions of invoking the image of a child's soft squeeze toy.<ref name=\"kitty-interview\"/> Some of the inspiration comes from [[Dr. Seuss]], with other inspiration from [[Saturday morning cartoon]]s.<ref name=\"kitty-interview\"/><ref name=\"armada\">{{cite web |url=http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=139420 |title=Meet the Master Chef&nbsp;\u2013 C.H. Greenblatt |date=December 12, 2007 |first=Steve |last=Fritz |publisher=Animated Shorts |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122105026/http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=139420 |archivedate=January 22, 2009 |accessdate=April 26, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nGreenblatt pitched the concept to Cartoon Network in the mid-2000s, when he began working as a writer and storyboard artist for ''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy]]'', and two years later the series was approved with another year for production before the pilot episode aired. Greenblatt estimates he spent about seven years working on ''Chowder'' before the show made it to air in 2007.<ref name=\"toonzone\"/>\n\n==Production and format==\nEpisodes are produced in seasons which consist of twenty 24-minute episodes. Each episode is produced with a 30-second puppet sequence that is meant to run over the ending credits.<ref name=\"season2\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/06/let-new-chowders-begin.html|title=Let the New Chowders Begin!!|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=June 3, 2008|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=June 4, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708054506/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/06/let-new-chowders-begin.html|archive-date=July 8, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Episodes can be purchased from the [[iTunes Store]] in the United States which are delivered with the sequences as are episodes which are available on Cartoon Network's VOD website also within the United States.<ref name=\"kitty-interview\"/><ref name=\"puppets\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/02/more-puppets.html|title=More Puppets|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=February 7, 2008|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=March 4, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203005913/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/02/more-puppets.html|archive-date=December 3, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOne of the unusual design features of the show is the patterns used on the clothing or players. The patterns are developed as a full-screen image and then sent to the production house, where the characters are modified to fill the patterns in over the character clothing.<ref name=\"toonzone\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonzone.net/2007/10/toon-zone-interviews-c-h-greenblatt-on-crafting-chowder/|title=Toon Zone Interviews C.H. Greenblatt on Crafting \"Chowder\"|first=Ed|last=Liu|date=October 30, 2007|publisher=Toon Zone|accessdate=March 4, 2008|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130703111526/http://www.toonzone.net/2007/10/toon-zone-interviews-c-h-greenblatt-on-crafting-chowder/|archive-date=July 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"kitty-interview\">{{cite web|url=http://kittysneezes.com/2008/02/08/interview-ch-greenblatt-207/|title=Interview: C.H. Greenblatt|first=Joe|last=Meyer|date=February 8, 2008|work=KittySneezes.com|accessdate=March 4, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116025642/http://kittysneezes.com/2008/02/08/interview-ch-greenblatt-207/|archive-date=January 16, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"patterns\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/01/chowder-patterns.html|title=Chowder Patterns|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=January 29, 2008|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=March 4, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516031555/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2008/01/chowder-patterns.html|archive-date=May 16, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> Using this technique, when a character moves, their patterns do not follow, but display as a \"static\" background. A similar technique was used in the ''[[Monkey Island (series)|Monkey Island]]'' video game series (particularly for the Stan), the Nickelodeon series [[The Off-Beats]], and the [[Mr. Bean (animated TV series)|''Mr. Bean'' animated series]].<ref name=\"armada\"/>\n\nThe show is also known for the very wide variety of media used in various episodes. These include animation using watercolors and ink-and-paint in addition to the cartoon's classic pattern style. It also uses stop motion animation with real food, action figures and clay; live-action scenes with the voice actors of the show and puppets; both marionette and hand-controlled. This was also sometimes used in ''[[Courage the Cowardly Dog]]''. It boasts one of the most diverse varieties of mediums used in any single series.\n\n==Cancellation==\n''Chowder'' was cancelled by Cartoon Network in August 2009, as the network felt the show did not fit its new demographic of older boys, favoring shows such as the live-action ''[[Destroy, Build, Destroy]]'' instead.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://chgreenblatt.tumblr.com/post/152842491532/you-mentioned-in-an-ask-that-you-went-through-the | title=Tumblr | access-date=November 15, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116103638/http://chgreenblatt.tumblr.com/post/152842491532/you-mentioned-in-an-ask-that-you-went-through-the | archive-date=November 16, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> On his blog, C.H. Greenblatt expressed relief about having his schedule freed up by the cancellation, saying: \"I didn't really think there'd be this many upsides to having a show officially cancelled by a network, but I'm feeling happier than I've been in a long time. Since we've only got post-production, my schedule finally eases up. I haven't had a break like this in a long, long time... ''Chowder'' has opened up a lot of awesome possibilities for me, and creatively I'm feeling more inspired than ever.\"<ref name=\"blogspot\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2009/08/hot-girl.html|title=The Hot Girl|first=C.H.|last=Greenblatt|date=August 13, 2009|work=Nerd Armada|accessdate=January 2, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311091937/http://nerdarmada.blogspot.com/2009/08/hot-girl.html|archive-date=March 11, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n|+''Chowder'' home video releases\n! colspan=3 rowspan=2|Season !! rowspan=2|Episodes !! rowspan=2|Volume !! colspan=2|Release dates !! rowspan=2|Episode(s) include\n|-\n! {{USA}} !! {{THA}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.toonzone.net/forums/threads/dvd-releases-from-mvd-in-thailand.5527321 |title=DVD releases from MVD in Thailand |access-date=April 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424214131/http://www.toonzone.net/forums/threads/dvd-releases-from-mvd-in-thailand.5527321/ |archive-date=April 24, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=5 style=\"background:#1E5994\"| || rowspan=5|[[List of Chowder episodes#Season 1 (2007\u201308)|1]]\n| rowspan=5|2007\u201308 || rowspan=5|20 || rowspan=2|1 || November 4, 2008<ref>{{cite web|asin=B001DSNFQ4|title=Chowder, Vol. 1 (2008)}}</ref> || rowspan=2|November 10, 2010 || rowspan=2|\"The Froggy Apple Crumple Thumpkin\" / \"Chowder's Girlfriend\" \u2022 \"Grubble Gum\" \u2013 \"The Sing Beans\" \u2022 \"Mahjongg Night\" \u2013 \"The Flibber-Flabber Diet\"\n|-\n| May 6, 2014\n|-\n| 2 || March 3, 2009<ref>{{cite web|asin=B001MEJYBY|title=Chowder, Vol. 2 (2009)}}</ref> || December 15, 2010 || \"Burple Nurples\" / \"Shnitzel Makes a Deposit\" \u2022 \"The Wrong Address\" / \"The Wrong Customer\" \u2022 \"Gazpacho Stands Up\" \u2013 \"Mung on the Rocks\"\n|-\n| 3 || {{n/a}} || January 19, 2010 || \"The Heavy Sleeper\" \u2013 \"The Rat Sandwich\"\n|-\n| 4 || {{n/a}} || February 15, 2011 || \"Chowder Loses His Hat\" \u2013 \"The Apprentice Games\"\n|-\n! rowspan=5 style=\"background:#5C1F99\"| || rowspan=5|[[List of Chowder episodes#Season 2 (2008\u201309)|2]]\n| rowspan=5|2008\u201309 || rowspan=5|20 || 5 || {{n/a}} || March 15, 2011 || \"The Arborians\" \u2013 \"The Catch Phrase\"\n|-\n| 6 || {{n/a}} || April 8, 2011 || \"The Hot Date\" \u2013 \"The Deadly Maze\" \u2022 \"The B.L.T.'s\" \u2013 \"The Dinner Theater\"\n|-\n| 7 || {{n/a}} || May 10, 2011 || \"Kid Shnitzel\" / \"Gazpacho Fights Back\" \u2022 \"Big Ball\" \u2013 \"The Blackout\"\n|-\n| 8 || {{n/a}} || June 14, 2011 || \"The Dice Cycle\" \u2013 \"The Grape Worm\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2|9 || rowspan=2 style=\"background:#ececec;color:#2d2d2d\"|<small>N/A</small> || rowspan=2|July 26, 2011 || rowspan=2| \"A Faire to Remember\" \u2013 \"The Birthday Suits\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 style=\"background:#991F5C\"| || rowspan=2|[[List of Chowder episodes#Season 3 (2009\u201310)|3]]\n| rowspan=2|2009\u201310 || rowspan=2|9\n|-\n| 10 || {{n/a}} || August 24, 2011 || \"The Heist\" \u2013 \"Chowder Grows Up\"\n|}\nThe entire series has been released in ten [[DVD region code#3|Region 3]] [[pan and scan|fullscreen]] DVD volumes in Thailand from MVD Company Limited.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critics===\nChowder received mostly positive reviews. Barry Garron of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' thought that the show would appeal to children and adults alike, using exotic artwork, unusual settings, and a zany cast of characters.<ref name=\"hollywood\">{{cite journal|url=http://208.115.47.50/cartoonnetwork/article_images/NXE913120_1_H.pdf |title=Chowder |first=Barry |last=Garron |date=November 2, 2007 |page=47 |journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5oDZGw1pO?url=http://208.115.47.50/cartoonnetwork/article_images/NXE913120_1_H.pdf |archivedate=March 14, 2010 |accessdate=April 26, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> On Toon Zone, Ed Liu expands on the animation and crazy antics of the characters, pointing that \"the humor is kid-friendly without being juvenile\" and praising it for getting laughs, \"without resorting to an excess of toilet humor, even if Chowder's pet happens to be a sentient fart cloud.\"<ref name=\"toonzone-review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonzone.net/2007/11/chowder-is-satisfying-comfort-food/|title=\"Chowder\" is Satisfying Comfort Food|first=Ed|last=Liu|date=November 2, 2007|publisher=Toon Zone|accessdate=February 18, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025005642/http://www.toonzone.net/2007/11/chowder-is-satisfying-comfort-food/|archive-date=October 25, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Aaron H. Bynum on ''Animation Insider'' wrote, \"Featuring brightly colored environments, stylishly matted/fixed background artwork and humorously designed characters with unique personalities to boot, ''Chowder'' is one of the network's largest creative accomplishments in recent years.\"<ref name=\"insider\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=1529|title=New 'Chowder' Animation Ready to Serve|first=Aaron H.|last=Bynum|date=October 24, 2007|work=Animation Insider|accessdate=February 18, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222150449/http://www.animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=1529|archive-date=December 22, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! '''Year'''\n! '''Association'''\n! '''Category'''\n! '''Recipient'''\n! '''Result'''\n|-\n| 2008\n| [[Annie Awards]]\n| Best Animated Television Production for Children<ref name=\"annies08\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/35th-annie-awards|title=35th Annual Annie Nominations and Awards Recipients|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=[[ASIFA-Hollywood]]|accessdate=March 4, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204082048/http://annieawards.org/35thwinners.html|archive-date=December 4, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| ''Chowder''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| Annie Awards\n| Writing in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"annies08\"/>\n| C.H. Greenblatt and William Reiss<br />{{small|for \"Burple Nurples\"}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| [[Emmy Awards]]\n| Outstanding Special Class&nbsp;\u2014 Short-format Animated Programs<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/chowder|title=Chowder|work=[[Emmys.com]]|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=July 9, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501003329/http://www.emmys.com/shows/chowder|archive-date=May 1, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| C.H. Greenblatt, [[Brian A. Miller]], et al.<br />{{small|for \"Burple Nurples\"}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| Annie Awards\n| Production Design in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"annies09\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/36th-annie-awards|title=36th Annual Annie Nominations and Awards Recipients|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|accessdate=July 9, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69zPVGfIi?url=http://annieawards.org/legacy36th.html|archive-date=August 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Dan Krall<br />{{small|for \"The Heavy Sleeper\"}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| Annie Awards\n| Voice Acting in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"annies09\"/>\n| Dwight Schultz<br />{{small|as Mung Daal}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| Emmy Awards\n| Outstanding Individual Achievement in Animation<ref name=\"emmys\"/>\n| Joe Binggeli\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| Annie Awards\n| Voice Acting in a Television Production<ref name=\"annies10\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/37th-annie-awards|title=37th Annual Annie Nominations and Awards Recipients|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|accessdate=July 9, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6OY2jk0n5?url=http://annieawards.org/37th-annie-awards|archive-date=April 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Nicky Jones<br />{{small|as Chowder}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| Annie Awards\n| Voice Acting in a Television Production<ref name=\"annies10\"/>\n| Dwight Schultz<br />{{small|as Mung Daal}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| Emmy Awards\n| Outstanding Short-format Animated Program<ref name=\"emmys\"/>\n| [[Brian A. Miller]], C.H. Greenblatt, et al.<br />{{small|for \"The Toots\"}}\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== Impact ==\nIn 2019, [[Lil Nas X]] made a music video of a remix of his song \"[[Panini (song)|Panini]]\" and named it after the ''Chowder'' character of the same name, and later made a music video for a remix of his song featuring characters from ''Chowder''. Although Greenblatt was not involved in the production of the music video, he did praise the video on his Tumblr blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chgreenblatt.tumblr.com/post/187682692082/did-you-have-any-involvement-with-lil-nas-xs-new|title=Nerd Armada|website=Nerd Armada|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=2019-10-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924201429/https://chgreenblatt.tumblr.com/post/187682692082/did-you-have-any-involvement-with-lil-nas-xs-new|archive-date=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Portal|Cartoon Network|Cartoon|Animation|United States|Television}}\n* {{IMDb title|1140100|Chowder}}\n* {{bcdb|Other_Studios/C/Cartoon_Network_Studios/Chowder/|Chowder}}\n* ''[http://www.tv.com/shows/chowder/ Chowder]'' at [[TV.com]]\n\n{{Cartoon Network original programming}}\n\n[[Category:Chowder (TV series)| ]]\n[[Category:2007 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American surreal comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American surreal comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American television programs featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about families]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network Studios series and characters]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Metafictional television series]]\n[[Category:Television series created by C. H. Greenblatt]]\n", "name_user": "173.177.178.28", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eImpact)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chowder_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Dean Trantalis", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dean Trantalis\n| office = 42nd [[List of mayors of Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Mayor of Fort Lauderdale]]\n| image = File:Linda Balent and Mayor Dean Trantalis (33155204688) (cropped).jpg\n| image name = \n| predecessor = [[Jack Seiler]]\n| termstart = March 20, 2018\n| office2 = Commissioner, Fort Lauderdale\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| termend2 = March 20, 2018\n| termstart2 = March 17, 2013\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1953|10|14}}\n| occupation = Lawyer\n}}\n\n'''Dean J. Trantalis''' (born October 14, 1953) is an American politician and mayor of [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]. Before his election as mayor, Trantalis served as a city commissioner for Fort Lauderdale from 2009 to 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fortlauderdale.gov/government/city-commission/commissioner-dean-trantalis|title=City of Fort Lauderdale, FL : Commissioner Dean J. Trantalis|website=www.fortlauderdale.gov|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> This mans definitely a pedo look at his face dude don\u2019t even lie person that changed it he looks like a child molester\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Fort Lauderdale City Commissioner (2003-2006) ===\nTrantalis was elected to the Fort Lauderdale City Commission in 2003, and served until 2006. He was the city's first openly gay commissioner.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dallasvoice.com/fort-lauderdale-elects-first-openly-gay-mayor-landslide-10250374.html|title=Fort Lauderdale Elects First Openly-Gay Mayor in Landslide - Dallas Voice|date=2018-03-14|work=Dallas Voice|access-date=2018-03-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Fort Lauderdale City Commission (2013-2018) ===\nTrantalis was elected to the Fort Lauderdale City Commission in a 2013 special election, defeating then-incumbent Charlotte Rodstrom, who instead ran for County Commission.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2013-03-13/news/fl-election-fort-lauderdale-district-2-20130312_1_dean-trantalis-charlotte-rodstrom-rodstrom-and-trantalis|title=Former Commissioner Dean Trantalis wins Fort Lauderdale special election|work=tribunedigital-sunsentinel|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> He won the 2015 general election without much opposition.\n\n==== \"Homeless Hate Laws\" ====\nThe City of Fort Lauderdale made international news when the commission voted to outlaw feeding the homeless.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fort-lauderdale/fl-lauderdale-homeless-feeding-sites-20141021-story.html|title=Fort Lauderdale commissioners pull all-nighter and approve homeless feeding restrictions|last=Barszewski|first=Larry|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Trantalis voted against the ordinance, causing a major rift between himself and the commission. There was international outrage when a 93-year-old man, Arnold Abbot, was arrested for feeding the homeless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.local10.com/news/local/fort-lauderdale/arnold-abbott-vows-to-continue-feeding-homeless-in-fort-lauderdale-despite-dwindling-funds|title=Arnold Abbott vows to continue feeding homeless in Fort...|last=Norman|first=Bob|website=www.local10.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> The City passed another feeding ban in 2017, despite public outcry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/fort-lauderdale-homeless-feeding-ban-proposed-again-9483644|title=Fort Lauderdale Wants to Ban Feeding the Homeless Again|last=Iannelli|first=Jerry|date=2017-07-10|work=Miami New Times|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> In 2016, the [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]] announced that it would probe [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] and the [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|City of Fort Lauderdale]], in response to the homeless sharing ordinances.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/news/homeless-hate-laws-in-broward-prompt-talk-that-the-department-of-justice-is-investigating-7757752|title=\"Homeless Hate Laws\" in Broward Prompt Talk That the Department of Justice Is Investigating|last=Funcheon|first=Deirdra|date=2016-05-06|work=New Times Broward-Palm Beach|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Trantalis has vowed that as Mayor, he would not enforce the ordinance.\n\n==== Development ====\nTrantalis has been an early opponent of overdevelopment in the coastal city. On the commission, he voted against many of the development proposals. In 2017, he voted against the controversial Bahia Mar development proposal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/news/bahia-mar-critics-say-developer-seemed-to-coach-city-commission-using-hand-signals-7854158|title=Bahia Mar: Critics Say Developer Seemed to \"Coach\" City Commission Using Hand Signals|last=Iannelli|first=Jerry|date=2016-06-17|work=New Times Broward-Palm Beach|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Fort Lauderdale Mayoral Election, 2018 ===\nThe 2018 race for mayor of Fort Lauderdale was said to be the city's most heated election. Trantalis announced his intent to run for mayor late in October 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fortlauderdaledaily.com/profiles/face-fort-lauderdale|title=The FACE of FORT LAUDERDALE|website=Fort Lauderdale Daily|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fort-lauderdale/fl-sb-fort-lauderdale-mayor-trantalis-20171016-story.html|title=Fort Lauderdale mayor race heats up|last=Wallman|first=Brittany|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> The election became about pressing issues such as development, infrastructure, traffic, and special interests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fl-sb-mayor-race-lauderdale-20180102-story.html|title=Development, broken pipes, traffic dominate mayor's race|last=Wallman|first=Brittany|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> \"Our infrastructure needs have reached a crisis level, and now we are discovering that mismanagement of city funds only made the situation worse\", said Trantalis in a [[Sun Sentinel]] questionnaire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/sfl-sun-sentinel-questionnaire-dean-trantalis-mayoral-race-20180102-story.html|title=Sun Sentinel questionnaire: Dean Trantalis, mayoral race|last=Sun-Sentinel|first=South Florida|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> On January 12, 2018, Trantalis campaign staffer Elijah Manley was arrested by the [[Fort Lauderdale Police Department]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.local10.com/news/local/fort-lauderdale/staffer-for-fort-lauderdale-mayoral-candidate-accused-of-tampering-with-signs|title=Staffer for Fort Lauderdale mayoral candidate accused of...|last=Swift|first=Tim|website=www.local10.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Manley was accused of tampering with campaign signs. On ''This Week in South Florida,'' Trantalis defended Manley, saying that it could have been because of a mistaken identity. Manley accused the Fort Lauderdale Police Department of a \"politically motivated\" arrest and bias for their former boss, Bruce Roberts, who was running against Trantalis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fort-lauderdale/fl-sb-mayor-race-lauderdale-20180117-story.html|title=Mayoral candidates slinging mud in Fort Lauderdale race|last=Wallman|first=Brittany|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Trantalis and Roberts exceed to a March 2018 runoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/other/trantalis-and-roberts-in-runoff-for-mayor-of-fort-lauderdale/ar-AAuPaRL|title=Trantalis and Roberts in runoff for mayor of Fort Lauderdale|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2018-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070458/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/other/trantalis-and-roberts-in-runoff-for-mayor-of-fort-lauderdale/ar-AAuPaRL|archive-date=2018-03-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Trantalis handily defeated Bruce Roberts, with a 64% landslide in the March 13th, 2018 General Election runoff.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fort-lauderdale/fl-reg-fort-lauderdale-new-mayor-20180312-story.html|title=Dean Trantalis is Fort Lauderdale's new mayor|last=Wallman|first=Brittany|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Trantalis is the first openly gay person to be elected Mayor of Fort Lauderdale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.local10.com/news/local/fort-lauderdale/dean-trantalis-makes-history-as-first-openly-gay-mayor-of-fort-lauderdale|title=Dean Trantalis makes history as first openly gay mayor of Fort...|last=Burke|first=Peter|website=www.local10.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDean Trantalis resides in Fort Lauderdale, Florida. He graduated with a law degree from [[Stetson University]] in St. Petersburg, Florida. He practices real estate law, and has his own private practice firm in real estate law.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jack Seiler]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Mayor of Fort Lauderdale]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Florida cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trantalis, Dean}}\n[[Category:Mayors of Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]\n[[Category:Florida lawyers]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Stetson University alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Florida]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dean Trantalis\n| office = 42nd [[List of mayors of Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Mayor of Fort Lauderdale]]\n| image = File:Linda Balent and Mayor Dean Trantalis (33155204688) (cropped).jpg\n| image name = \n| predecessor = [[Jack Seiler]]\n| termstart = March 20, 2018\n| office2 = Commissioner, Fort Lauderdale\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| termend2 = March 20, 2018\n| termstart2 = March 17, 2013\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1953|10|14}}\n| occupation = Lawyer\n}}\n\n'''Dean J. Trantalis''' (born October 14, 1953) is an American politician and mayor of [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]. Before his election as mayor, Trantalis served as a city commissioner for Fort Lauderdale from 2009 to 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fortlauderdale.gov/government/city-commission/commissioner-dean-trantalis|title=City of Fort Lauderdale, FL : Commissioner Dean J. Trantalis|website=www.fortlauderdale.gov|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Fort Lauderdale City Commissioner (2003-2006) ===\nTrantalis was elected to the Fort Lauderdale City Commission in 2003, and served until 2006. He was the city's first openly gay commissioner.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dallasvoice.com/fort-lauderdale-elects-first-openly-gay-mayor-landslide-10250374.html|title=Fort Lauderdale Elects First Openly-Gay Mayor in Landslide - Dallas Voice|date=2018-03-14|work=Dallas Voice|access-date=2018-03-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Fort Lauderdale City Commission (2013-2018) ===\nTrantalis was elected to the Fort Lauderdale City Commission in a 2013 special election, defeating then-incumbent Charlotte Rodstrom, who instead ran for County Commission.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2013-03-13/news/fl-election-fort-lauderdale-district-2-20130312_1_dean-trantalis-charlotte-rodstrom-rodstrom-and-trantalis|title=Former Commissioner Dean Trantalis wins Fort Lauderdale special election|work=tribunedigital-sunsentinel|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> He won the 2015 general election without much opposition.\n\n==== \"Homeless Hate Laws\" ====\nThe City of Fort Lauderdale made international news when the commission voted to outlaw feeding the homeless.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fort-lauderdale/fl-lauderdale-homeless-feeding-sites-20141021-story.html|title=Fort Lauderdale commissioners pull all-nighter and approve homeless feeding restrictions|last=Barszewski|first=Larry|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Trantalis voted against the ordinance, causing a major rift between himself and the commission. There was international outrage when a 93-year-old man, Arnold Abbot, was arrested for feeding the homeless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.local10.com/news/local/fort-lauderdale/arnold-abbott-vows-to-continue-feeding-homeless-in-fort-lauderdale-despite-dwindling-funds|title=Arnold Abbott vows to continue feeding homeless in Fort...|last=Norman|first=Bob|website=www.local10.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> The City passed another feeding ban in 2017, despite public outcry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/fort-lauderdale-homeless-feeding-ban-proposed-again-9483644|title=Fort Lauderdale Wants to Ban Feeding the Homeless Again|last=Iannelli|first=Jerry|date=2017-07-10|work=Miami New Times|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> In 2016, the [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]] announced that it would probe [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] and the [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|City of Fort Lauderdale]], in response to the homeless sharing ordinances.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/news/homeless-hate-laws-in-broward-prompt-talk-that-the-department-of-justice-is-investigating-7757752|title=\"Homeless Hate Laws\" in Broward Prompt Talk That the Department of Justice Is Investigating|last=Funcheon|first=Deirdra|date=2016-05-06|work=New Times Broward-Palm Beach|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Trantalis has vowed that as Mayor, he would not enforce the ordinance.\n\n==== Development ====\nTrantalis has been an early opponent of overdevelopment in the coastal city. On the commission, he voted against many of the development proposals. In 2017, he voted against the controversial Bahia Mar development proposal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/news/bahia-mar-critics-say-developer-seemed-to-coach-city-commission-using-hand-signals-7854158|title=Bahia Mar: Critics Say Developer Seemed to \"Coach\" City Commission Using Hand Signals|last=Iannelli|first=Jerry|date=2016-06-17|work=New Times Broward-Palm Beach|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Fort Lauderdale Mayoral Election, 2018 ===\nThe 2018 race for mayor of Fort Lauderdale was said to be the city's most heated election. Trantalis announced his intent to run for mayor late in October 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fortlauderdaledaily.com/profiles/face-fort-lauderdale|title=The FACE of FORT LAUDERDALE|website=Fort Lauderdale Daily|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fort-lauderdale/fl-sb-fort-lauderdale-mayor-trantalis-20171016-story.html|title=Fort Lauderdale mayor race heats up|last=Wallman|first=Brittany|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> The election became about pressing issues such as development, infrastructure, traffic, and special interests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fl-sb-mayor-race-lauderdale-20180102-story.html|title=Development, broken pipes, traffic dominate mayor's race|last=Wallman|first=Brittany|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> \"Our infrastructure needs have reached a crisis level, and now we are discovering that mismanagement of city funds only made the situation worse\", said Trantalis in a [[Sun Sentinel]] questionnaire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/sfl-sun-sentinel-questionnaire-dean-trantalis-mayoral-race-20180102-story.html|title=Sun Sentinel questionnaire: Dean Trantalis, mayoral race|last=Sun-Sentinel|first=South Florida|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> On January 12, 2018, Trantalis campaign staffer Elijah Manley was arrested by the [[Fort Lauderdale Police Department]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.local10.com/news/local/fort-lauderdale/staffer-for-fort-lauderdale-mayoral-candidate-accused-of-tampering-with-signs|title=Staffer for Fort Lauderdale mayoral candidate accused of...|last=Swift|first=Tim|website=www.local10.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Manley was accused of tampering with campaign signs. On ''This Week in South Florida,'' Trantalis defended Manley, saying that it could have been because of a mistaken identity. Manley accused the Fort Lauderdale Police Department of a \"politically motivated\" arrest and bias for their former boss, Bruce Roberts, who was running against Trantalis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fort-lauderdale/fl-sb-mayor-race-lauderdale-20180117-story.html|title=Mayoral candidates slinging mud in Fort Lauderdale race|last=Wallman|first=Brittany|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Trantalis and Roberts exceed to a March 2018 runoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/other/trantalis-and-roberts-in-runoff-for-mayor-of-fort-lauderdale/ar-AAuPaRL|title=Trantalis and Roberts in runoff for mayor of Fort Lauderdale|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2018-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070458/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/other/trantalis-and-roberts-in-runoff-for-mayor-of-fort-lauderdale/ar-AAuPaRL|archive-date=2018-03-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Trantalis handily defeated Bruce Roberts, with a 64% landslide in the March 13th, 2018 General Election runoff.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fort-lauderdale/fl-reg-fort-lauderdale-new-mayor-20180312-story.html|title=Dean Trantalis is Fort Lauderdale's new mayor|last=Wallman|first=Brittany|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> Trantalis is the first openly gay person to be elected Mayor of Fort Lauderdale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.local10.com/news/local/fort-lauderdale/dean-trantalis-makes-history-as-first-openly-gay-mayor-of-fort-lauderdale|title=Dean Trantalis makes history as first openly gay mayor of Fort...|last=Burke|first=Peter|website=www.local10.com|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDean Trantalis resides in Fort Lauderdale, Florida. He graduated with a law degree from [[Stetson University]] in St. Petersburg, Florida. He practices real estate law, and has his own private practice firm in real estate law.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jack Seiler]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Mayor of Fort Lauderdale]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Florida cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trantalis, Dean}}\n[[Category:Mayors of Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]\n[[Category:Florida lawyers]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Stetson University alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Florida]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "2001:bb6:517b:4f58:d57f:2814:7a21:84db", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dean_Trantalis"}
{"title_page": "Orthopathy", "text_new": "{{Alternative medical systems|fringe}}\n'''Orthopathy''' (from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u1f40\u03c1\u03b8\u03cc\u03c2 ''orthos'' \"right\" and \u03c0\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2 ''pathos'' \"suffering\") or '''Natural Hygiene''' ('''NH''') is not a set of [[alternative medicine|alternative medical]] beliefs.It is a set of practices originating from the ''Nature Cure'' movement. \n\n\n\n== History and practice ==\n\n===19th century===\n\nThe orthopathy movement originated with [[Isaac Jennings]] in the 1820s, who practiced conventional medicine for many years but became discouraged with its results.<ref name=orcutt>Orcutt, Samuel; Beardsley, Ambrose. (1880). [https://archive.org/details/historyofoldtown00orcu/page/600 ''The History of the Old Town of Derby, Connecticut, 1642-1880. With Biographies and Genealogies'']. Press of Springfield Printing Company. pp. 601-603</ref><ref name=\"Lelieveld 2005\">Lelieveld, H. L. M; Holah, John; Mostert, M. A. (2005). ''Handbook of Hygiene Control in the Food Industry''. Woodhead Publishing Limited. pp. 3-4. {{ISBN|978-1-85573-957-4}}</ref> Jennings' system was firmly opposed to all medicine and was known as the \"no-medicine plan\".<ref name=\"Lelieveld 2005\"/><ref name=\"Whorton 2016\">Whorton, James C. (2016 edition). ''Crusaders for Fitness: The History of American Health Reformers''. Princeton University Press. pp. 135-136. {{ISBN|978-0691641898}}</ref> He prescribed bathing, rest and a vegetarian diet as part of his system.<ref>Fletcher, Robert Samuel. (1943). [https://archive.org/details/historyofoberlin01flet/page/332 ''A History of Oberlin College From its Foundation Through the Civil War'']. Oberlin College. p. 332</ref><ref>Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). ''Vegetarian America: A History''. Praeger Publishing. pp. 28-29. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref>\n\nIn 1837, Colonel John Benson, [[Sylvester Graham]] and [[William Alcott]] founded the American Physiological Society (APS) in [[Boston]] to promote Grahamism, which lasted just three years.<ref name=\"BMJ\">{{cite journal|title=An American \"Physiological\" Society Of 1837|journal=The British Medical Journal|date=January 1, 1938|volume=2|issue=4057|pages=757|jstor=20300989}}</ref><ref name=\"Iacobbo 2004\">Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). ''Vegetarian America: A History''. Praeger Publishing. pp. 36-38. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref> The APS was the first natural hygiene organization in the United States.<ref name=\"Iacobbo 2004\"/> [[Mary Gove Nichols]] lectured for the Ladies Physiological Society, an off-shoot of the APS.<ref name=\"Iacobbo 2004\"/> In the 1840s, [[Joel Shew]] was influenced by the dieting ideas of Sylvester Graham and promoted natural hygiene practices such as bathing, exercise and massage as well as the elimination of [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] and [[tobacco]].<ref name=\"Engs 2000\">Engs, Ruth Clifford. (2000). ''Clean Living Movements: American Cycles of Health Reform''. Greenwood Publishing Group. p. 96. {{ISBN|0-275-97541-X}}</ref>\n\nIsaac Jennings in his 1867 book ''The Tree of Life'', defined orthopathy as \"from orthos, right, true, erect; and pathos, affection. Nature is always upright\u2014moving in the right direction.\"<ref name=\"Whorton 2016\"/> [[George H. Taylor (physician)|George H. Taylor]] who introduced [[Swedish massage]] to the United States in the 1860s was known to promote natural hygiene and [[physical culture]]. Taylor believed that correct breathing and diet, [[gymnastics]] and mechanical massage could replace medical intervention and restore health.<ref>Weber, Jody Marie. (2009). ''The Evolution of Aesthetic and Expressive Dance in Boston''. Cambria Press. p. 43. {{ISBN|978-1-60497-621-2}}</ref><ref>Braun, Mary Beth. (2014). Introduction to Massage Therapy, Third Edition. Lippincott Williams & Wilkins. p. 13. {{ISBN|978-1-4511-7319-2}}</ref>\n\nNatural hygiene was often associated with [[vegetarianism]] during the nineteenth century. However, not all natural hygienists are vegetarians.<ref>Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). ''Vegetarian America: A History''. Praeger Publishing. p. 104. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref> [[Russell T. Trall]] was a notable early proponent of natural hygiene and vegetarianism. Trall established his own version called \"hygeiotherapy\", a mixture of [[hydrotherapy]] with diet and exercise treatment regimes.<ref>Baer, Hans A. (2001). ''Biomedicine and Alternative Healing Systems in America: Issues of Class, Race, Ethnicity and Gender''. University of Wisconsin Press. p. 86. {{ISBN|0-299-16694-5}}</ref> \n\nIn 1887, [[Susanna Way Dodds]] and her sister Mary established the Hygienic College of Physicians and Surgeons in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].<ref>Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). Vegetarian America: A History. Praeger Publishing. p. 118. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref><ref name=\"Fisher 2008\">Fisher, Carol. (2008). ''Pot Roast, Politics, and Ants in the Pantry: Missouri's Cookbook Heritage''. University Of Missouri Press. pp. 19-20. {{ISBN|978-0-8262-1791-2}}</ref> They focused on \"natural methods of treatment: diet, exercise, massage, electricity and hydrotherapy in all of its manifold applications\".<ref name=\"Fisher 2008\"/>\n\nDuring the 1880s, [[Thomas Allinson]] developed his theory of medicine, which he called 'Hygienic Medicine.'\n\n===20th century===\n\nNatural hygienist [[George S. Weger]] managed Weger Health School in [[Redlands, California]] (1923-1935).<ref>Anonymous. (1936). ''Bulletin of the University of Maryland School of Medicine 1935-1936''. University of Maryland School of Medicine. p. 48</ref>\n\n[[Herbert M. Shelton]] who has been described as \"the twentieth century's premier natural hygienist\", was influenced by Sylvester Graham and Russell T. Trall.<ref>Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). ''Vegetarian America: A History''. Praeger Publishing. p. 160. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref> Shelton wrote much on the topic, beginning with ''The Hygienic System: Orthopathy''<ref name=SheltonVI>Herbert M Shelton, The Hygienic System vol. VI: Orthopathy, Dr. Shelton's Health School: San Antonio, Texas, 1941</ref> in 1939, which renamed orthopathy as 'Natural Hygiene.'\n\nConsumption of 'incompatible' foods in one meal is said to lead to ill health, and consumption of 'compatible' foods is said to maintain it: Shelton defined [[food combining]] and seven groups of food, sorted by function as: supplying energy (carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) needed to build the body (proteins, salts, and water) and regulating bodily processes (minerals, vitamins, and water.)<ref name=QW-NH />\n\nWhite supremacist [[Ben Klassen]] was influenced by Shelton and natural hygienic principles and promoted his own \"racial health\" regimen known as Salubrious Living.<ref name=\"Love 2016\">Love, Nancy S. (2016). ''Trendy Fascism: White Power Music and the Future of Democracy''. State University of New York Press. pp. 112-114. {{ISBN|978-1438462035}}</ref><ref name=\"Berry 2017\">Berry, Damon T. (2017). ''Blood and Faith: Christianity in American White Nationalism''. Syracuse University Press. pp. 92-93. {{ISBN|978-0-8156-3544-4}}</ref> However, Klassen emphasised there were differences between his doctrine and the natural hygiene movement as the latter did not focus on perpetuating the white race like his regimen did.<ref name=\"Berry 2017\"/> Klassen co-authored the book ''Salubrious Living'' with [[Arnold DeVries]] in 1982.<ref name=\"Love 2016\"/>\n\nInterest in natural hygiene was renewed in the 1980s following publication of ''[[Fit for Life]]'' and ''Living Health'' by Harvey and [[Marilyn Diamond]].<ref name=QW-NH />\n\n===Organizations===\n\nIn 1948, the American Natural Hygiene Society (ANHS) was founded by Herbert Shelton, William Esser, Gerald Benesh, Christopher Gian-Cursio, [[Jesse Mercer Gehman]], Irving Davidson, Jack Dunn Trop and [[Symon Gould]].<ref>[https://www.healthscience.org/heritage/anhsnha-history/timeline \"National Health Association Timeline\"]. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref> In 1998, the ANHS became the National Health Association.<ref>[https://www.healthscience.org/heritage \"History of the National Health Association\"]. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn 1956, Keki Sidhwa established the British Natural Hygiene Society (BNHS).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180926061304/http://www.drsidhwa.com/bnhs/ \"British Natural Hygiene Society\"]. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/dr-keki-sidhwa-92-energetic-advocate-of-natural-cures-27qf8vlb9 \"Dr Keki Sidhwa, 92: Energetic advocate of natural cures\"]. ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe International Association of Hygienic Physicians was founded in 1978.<ref name=QW-NH /> The International Natural Hygiene Society was founded in 2003 and has reported over 800 members.<ref name=QW-NH />\n\n==Criticism==\n\nMedical experts consider natural hygiene practices such as [[anti-vaccination]], fasting and food combining to be [[quackery]].<ref name=QW-NH/><ref name=\"Pepper 1984\">Pepper, Claude. (1984). [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pur1.32754066766001;view=1up;seq=104 ''Quackery: A $10 Billion Dollar Scandal'']. U.S. Government Printing Office. p. 94</ref><ref>[https://skeptoid.com/episodes/4028 \"Natural Hygiene: Health Without Medicine (or Wisdom)\"]. Retrieved 14 June 2019.</ref> There is no scientific evidence that prolonged fasting provides any significant health benefits.<ref name=\"Pepper 1984\"/><ref>Kuske, Terrence T. (1983). ''Quackery and Fad Diets''. In Elaine B. Feldman. ''Nutrition in the Middle and Later Years''. John Wright & Sons. pp. 291-303. {{ISBN|0-7236-7046-3}}</ref><ref name=\"Barrett 1993\">Barrett, Stephen; Jarvis, William T. (1993). ''The Health Robbers: A Close Look at Quackery in America''. Prometheus Books. p. 114. {{ISBN|0-87975-855-4}}</ref> A prolonged fast may cause \"anemia, impairment of liver function, kidney stones, postural hypotension, mineral imbalances, and other undesirable side effects.\"<ref name=\"Barrett 1993\"/>\n\nClaims from natural hygienists about fasting curing [[cancer]] are not supported by scientific evidence. According to the [[American Cancer Society]], \"available scientific evidence does not support claims that fasting is effective for preventing or treating cancer in humans.\"<ref>Russell J, Rovere A, eds. (2009). ''Fasting''. American Cancer Society Complete Guide to Complementary and Alternative Cancer Therapies (2nd ed.). American Cancer Society. {{ISBN|9780944235713}}.</ref>\n\n==Founders==\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\">\nIsaac Jennings.png|[[Isaac Jennings]]\nSylvester Graham LCCN99406591.jpg|[[Sylvester Graham]]\nJoel Shew.png|[[Joel Shew]]\nGeorge H. Taylor physician.png|[[George H. Taylor (physician)|George H. Taylor]]\nMary Gove Nichols.png|[[Mary Gove Nichols]]\nSusanna Way Dodds 1893.png|[[Susanna Way Dodds]]\nGeorge S. Weger 1903.png|[[George S. Weger]] \n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of orthopaths]]\n* [[Naturopathy]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Alternative medicine|state=collapsed}}\n{{Fad diets|state=collapsed}}\n{{Veganism and vegetarianism|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Alternative detoxification]]\n[[Category:Alternative medical systems]]\n[[Category:Fad diets]]\n[[Category:Fasting]]\n[[Category:History of vegetarianism]]\n[[Category:Orthopathy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Alternative medical systems|fringe}}\n'''Orthopathy''' (from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u1f40\u03c1\u03b8\u03cc\u03c2 ''orthos'' \"right\" and \u03c0\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2 ''pathos'' \"suffering\") or '''Natural Hygiene''' ('''NH''') is a set of [[alternative medicine|alternative medical]] beliefs and practices originating from the ''Nature Cure'' movement. Proponents claim that [[fasting]], dieting, and other lifestyle measures are all that is necessary to prevent and treat disease.<ref name=QW-NH>{{cite web|url=http://www.quackwatch.org/01QuackeryRelatedTopics/natural_hygiene.html |title=A Critical Look at \"Natural Hygiene\" |accessdate=2009-04-15 |last=Barrett |first=Stephen |date=2007-01-01 }}</ref>\n\nNatural hygiene is an offshoot of [[naturopathy]] that advocates a philosophy of \"natural living\" that was developed in the early nineteenth century. Natural hygienists oppose drugs, [[fluoridation]], [[immunization]], most medical treatments and endorse fasting, [[food combining]] and [[Raw foodism|raw food]] or vegetarian diets.<ref name=QW-NH/><ref>Barrett, Stephen; Herbert, Victor. ''Questionable Practices in Foods and Nutrition: Definitions and Descriptions''. (2002). In Carolyn D. Berdanier. ''Handbook of Nutrition and Food''. CRC Press. p. 1493. {{ISBN|0-8493-2705-9}}</ref>\n\n== History and practice ==\n\n===19th century===\n\nThe orthopathy movement originated with [[Isaac Jennings]] in the 1820s, who practiced conventional medicine for many years but became discouraged with its results.<ref name=orcutt>Orcutt, Samuel; Beardsley, Ambrose. (1880). [https://archive.org/details/historyofoldtown00orcu/page/600 ''The History of the Old Town of Derby, Connecticut, 1642-1880. With Biographies and Genealogies'']. Press of Springfield Printing Company. pp. 601-603</ref><ref name=\"Lelieveld 2005\">Lelieveld, H. L. M; Holah, John; Mostert, M. A. (2005). ''Handbook of Hygiene Control in the Food Industry''. Woodhead Publishing Limited. pp. 3-4. {{ISBN|978-1-85573-957-4}}</ref> Jennings' system was firmly opposed to all medicine and was known as the \"no-medicine plan\".<ref name=\"Lelieveld 2005\"/><ref name=\"Whorton 2016\">Whorton, James C. (2016 edition). ''Crusaders for Fitness: The History of American Health Reformers''. Princeton University Press. pp. 135-136. {{ISBN|978-0691641898}}</ref> He prescribed bathing, rest and a vegetarian diet as part of his system.<ref>Fletcher, Robert Samuel. (1943). [https://archive.org/details/historyofoberlin01flet/page/332 ''A History of Oberlin College From its Foundation Through the Civil War'']. Oberlin College. p. 332</ref><ref>Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). ''Vegetarian America: A History''. Praeger Publishing. pp. 28-29. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref>\n\nIn 1837, Colonel John Benson, [[Sylvester Graham]] and [[William Alcott]] founded the American Physiological Society (APS) in [[Boston]] to promote Grahamism, which lasted just three years.<ref name=\"BMJ\">{{cite journal|title=An American \"Physiological\" Society Of 1837|journal=The British Medical Journal|date=January 1, 1938|volume=2|issue=4057|pages=757|jstor=20300989}}</ref><ref name=\"Iacobbo 2004\">Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). ''Vegetarian America: A History''. Praeger Publishing. pp. 36-38. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref> The APS was the first natural hygiene organization in the United States.<ref name=\"Iacobbo 2004\"/> [[Mary Gove Nichols]] lectured for the Ladies Physiological Society, an off-shoot of the APS.<ref name=\"Iacobbo 2004\"/> In the 1840s, [[Joel Shew]] was influenced by the dieting ideas of Sylvester Graham and promoted natural hygiene practices such as bathing, exercise and massage as well as the elimination of [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] and [[tobacco]].<ref name=\"Engs 2000\">Engs, Ruth Clifford. (2000). ''Clean Living Movements: American Cycles of Health Reform''. Greenwood Publishing Group. p. 96. {{ISBN|0-275-97541-X}}</ref>\n\nIsaac Jennings in his 1867 book ''The Tree of Life'', defined orthopathy as \"from orthos, right, true, erect; and pathos, affection. Nature is always upright\u2014moving in the right direction.\"<ref name=\"Whorton 2016\"/> [[George H. Taylor (physician)|George H. Taylor]] who introduced [[Swedish massage]] to the United States in the 1860s was known to promote natural hygiene and [[physical culture]]. Taylor believed that correct breathing and diet, [[gymnastics]] and mechanical massage could replace medical intervention and restore health.<ref>Weber, Jody Marie. (2009). ''The Evolution of Aesthetic and Expressive Dance in Boston''. Cambria Press. p. 43. {{ISBN|978-1-60497-621-2}}</ref><ref>Braun, Mary Beth. (2014). Introduction to Massage Therapy, Third Edition. Lippincott Williams & Wilkins. p. 13. {{ISBN|978-1-4511-7319-2}}</ref>\n\nNatural hygiene was often associated with [[vegetarianism]] during the nineteenth century. However, not all natural hygienists are vegetarians.<ref>Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). ''Vegetarian America: A History''. Praeger Publishing. p. 104. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref> [[Russell T. Trall]] was a notable early proponent of natural hygiene and vegetarianism. Trall established his own version called \"hygeiotherapy\", a mixture of [[hydrotherapy]] with diet and exercise treatment regimes.<ref>Baer, Hans A. (2001). ''Biomedicine and Alternative Healing Systems in America: Issues of Class, Race, Ethnicity and Gender''. University of Wisconsin Press. p. 86. {{ISBN|0-299-16694-5}}</ref> \n\nIn 1887, [[Susanna Way Dodds]] and her sister Mary established the Hygienic College of Physicians and Surgeons in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].<ref>Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). Vegetarian America: A History. Praeger Publishing. p. 118. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref><ref name=\"Fisher 2008\">Fisher, Carol. (2008). ''Pot Roast, Politics, and Ants in the Pantry: Missouri's Cookbook Heritage''. University Of Missouri Press. pp. 19-20. {{ISBN|978-0-8262-1791-2}}</ref> They focused on \"natural methods of treatment: diet, exercise, massage, electricity and hydrotherapy in all of its manifold applications\".<ref name=\"Fisher 2008\"/>\n\nDuring the 1880s, [[Thomas Allinson]] developed his theory of medicine, which he called 'Hygienic Medicine.'\n\n===20th century===\n\nNatural hygienist [[George S. Weger]] managed Weger Health School in [[Redlands, California]] (1923-1935).<ref>Anonymous. (1936). ''Bulletin of the University of Maryland School of Medicine 1935-1936''. University of Maryland School of Medicine. p. 48</ref>\n\n[[Herbert M. Shelton]] who has been described as \"the twentieth century's premier natural hygienist\", was influenced by Sylvester Graham and Russell T. Trall.<ref>Iacobbo, Karen; Iacobbo, Michael. (2004). ''Vegetarian America: A History''. Praeger Publishing. p. 160. {{ISBN|978-0275975197}}</ref> Shelton wrote much on the topic, beginning with ''The Hygienic System: Orthopathy''<ref name=SheltonVI>Herbert M Shelton, The Hygienic System vol. VI: Orthopathy, Dr. Shelton's Health School: San Antonio, Texas, 1941</ref> in 1939, which renamed orthopathy as 'Natural Hygiene.'\n\nConsumption of 'incompatible' foods in one meal is said to lead to ill health, and consumption of 'compatible' foods is said to maintain it: Shelton defined [[food combining]] and seven groups of food, sorted by function as: supplying energy (carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) needed to build the body (proteins, salts, and water) and regulating bodily processes (minerals, vitamins, and water.)<ref name=QW-NH />\n\nWhite supremacist [[Ben Klassen]] was influenced by Shelton and natural hygienic principles and promoted his own \"racial health\" regimen known as Salubrious Living.<ref name=\"Love 2016\">Love, Nancy S. (2016). ''Trendy Fascism: White Power Music and the Future of Democracy''. State University of New York Press. pp. 112-114. {{ISBN|978-1438462035}}</ref><ref name=\"Berry 2017\">Berry, Damon T. (2017). ''Blood and Faith: Christianity in American White Nationalism''. Syracuse University Press. pp. 92-93. {{ISBN|978-0-8156-3544-4}}</ref> However, Klassen emphasised there were differences between his doctrine and the natural hygiene movement as the latter did not focus on perpetuating the white race like his regimen did.<ref name=\"Berry 2017\"/> Klassen co-authored the book ''Salubrious Living'' with [[Arnold DeVries]] in 1982.<ref name=\"Love 2016\"/>\n\nInterest in natural hygiene was renewed in the 1980s following publication of ''[[Fit for Life]]'' and ''Living Health'' by Harvey and [[Marilyn Diamond]].<ref name=QW-NH />\n\n===Organizations===\n\nIn 1948, the American Natural Hygiene Society (ANHS) was founded by Herbert Shelton, William Esser, Gerald Benesh, Christopher Gian-Cursio, [[Jesse Mercer Gehman]], Irving Davidson, Jack Dunn Trop and [[Symon Gould]].<ref>[https://www.healthscience.org/heritage/anhsnha-history/timeline \"National Health Association Timeline\"]. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref> In 1998, the ANHS became the National Health Association.<ref>[https://www.healthscience.org/heritage \"History of the National Health Association\"]. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn 1956, Keki Sidhwa established the British Natural Hygiene Society (BNHS).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180926061304/http://www.drsidhwa.com/bnhs/ \"British Natural Hygiene Society\"]. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/dr-keki-sidhwa-92-energetic-advocate-of-natural-cures-27qf8vlb9 \"Dr Keki Sidhwa, 92: Energetic advocate of natural cures\"]. ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe International Association of Hygienic Physicians was founded in 1978.<ref name=QW-NH /> The International Natural Hygiene Society was founded in 2003 and has reported over 800 members.<ref name=QW-NH />\n\n==Criticism==\n\nMedical experts consider natural hygiene practices such as [[anti-vaccination]], fasting and food combining to be [[quackery]].<ref name=QW-NH/><ref name=\"Pepper 1984\">Pepper, Claude. (1984). [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pur1.32754066766001;view=1up;seq=104 ''Quackery: A $10 Billion Dollar Scandal'']. U.S. Government Printing Office. p. 94</ref><ref>[https://skeptoid.com/episodes/4028 \"Natural Hygiene: Health Without Medicine (or Wisdom)\"]. Retrieved 14 June 2019.</ref> There is no scientific evidence that prolonged fasting provides any significant health benefits.<ref name=\"Pepper 1984\"/><ref>Kuske, Terrence T. (1983). ''Quackery and Fad Diets''. In Elaine B. Feldman. ''Nutrition in the Middle and Later Years''. John Wright & Sons. pp. 291-303. {{ISBN|0-7236-7046-3}}</ref><ref name=\"Barrett 1993\">Barrett, Stephen; Jarvis, William T. (1993). ''The Health Robbers: A Close Look at Quackery in America''. Prometheus Books. p. 114. {{ISBN|0-87975-855-4}}</ref> A prolonged fast may cause \"anemia, impairment of liver function, kidney stones, postural hypotension, mineral imbalances, and other undesirable side effects.\"<ref name=\"Barrett 1993\"/>\n\nClaims from natural hygienists about fasting curing [[cancer]] are not supported by scientific evidence. According to the [[American Cancer Society]], \"available scientific evidence does not support claims that fasting is effective for preventing or treating cancer in humans.\"<ref>Russell J, Rovere A, eds. (2009). ''Fasting''. American Cancer Society Complete Guide to Complementary and Alternative Cancer Therapies (2nd ed.). American Cancer Society. {{ISBN|9780944235713}}.</ref>\n\n==Founders==\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\">\nIsaac Jennings.png|[[Isaac Jennings]]\nSylvester Graham LCCN99406591.jpg|[[Sylvester Graham]]\nJoel Shew.png|[[Joel Shew]]\nGeorge H. Taylor physician.png|[[George H. Taylor (physician)|George H. Taylor]]\nMary Gove Nichols.png|[[Mary Gove Nichols]]\nSusanna Way Dodds 1893.png|[[Susanna Way Dodds]]\nGeorge S. Weger 1903.png|[[George S. Weger]] \n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of orthopaths]]\n* [[Naturopathy]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Alternative medicine|state=collapsed}}\n{{Fad diets|state=collapsed}}\n{{Veganism and vegetarianism|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Alternative detoxification]]\n[[Category:Alternative medical systems]]\n[[Category:Fad diets]]\n[[Category:Fasting]]\n[[Category:History of vegetarianism]]\n[[Category:Orthopathy]]\n", "name_user": "Ash Holliday", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Replaced uneducated comments.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthopathy"}
{"title_page": "List of news media APIs", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Orphan|date=December 2016}}\n\nSome [[online news media]] have created [[Application Programming Interface]]s (APIs) to enable computer applications to request stories and information about their stories ([[metadata]]) from them.\n\n== List of 1st-party news APIs ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! News organization || API home page || APIs || Note\n\n|-\n| [[American Broadcasting Company]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150909150340/http://developer.abc.com/docs/read/resources ABC Resources API]  || Resources API || Resources API retrieves content produced by ABC businesses, including national and local news, entertainment videos, and more.\n\n|-\n| [[Associated Press]] || [https://developer.ap.org/ AP Content API] \n|| \n* AP Content API\n* AP Breaking News API\n || \n* AP Content API allows the search and download of AP Images, one of the world\u2019s largest collections of historical and contemporary imagery.\n* AP Breaking News API retrieve a list of available breaking news categories and then requests content for a specific category.\n* Headlines and images only. Does not provide full text of articles.\n\n|-\n| [[BBC]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150810230518/https://developer.bbc.co.uk/content/bbc-platform-api BBC Platform API] [ Currently available only to BBC emplyees ] || Platform API || \n\"Platform API power all the BBC's product areas - iPlayer, News, Sport, Weather, Children's Knowledge and Learning - as well as many external and partner products such as Youview.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Billings|first1=Jon|title=Introducing Platform API|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/internet/entries/73c4f082-095f-3bf3-b4f0-53900e34a72b|accessdate=13 April 2015|date=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Bloomberg News]] || [http://www.bloomberglabs.com/api/ Bloomberg API] || Bloomberg API || Bloomberg API provides unrestricted access to raw data for customers for its financial market information. \n|-\n\n|-\n\n| [[CBS Sports]] || [http://developer.cbssports.com/documentation/ CBS Sports Development Center] [No longer available]||\n\n* Fantasy Live Scoring API\n* Rules API\n* Player Search API\n* Player Profile API\n* League Roster API\n* Schedule API\n* Salary and Wild Cards API\n* Playoff Settings API\n* Playoff Bracket API\n || \n* Fantasy Scoring API retrieves live scoring data for league.\n* Rules API retrieves rules for a fantasy league.\n* Player Search API retrieves a list of players.\n*Player Profile API retrieves a player's profile.\n* League Roster API retrieves roster for one team or all teams.\n* Schedule API retrieves schedule and match information.\n* Salary and Wild Cards API retrieve wildcard values for a set of players.\n* Playoff Settings API retrieves playoff settings for a league.\n* Playoff Bracket API retrieves a league\u2019s playoff bracket.\n\n|-\n| [[Die Zeit]] || [http://developer.zeit.de/index/ ZEIT ONLINE Content API] || Online Content API || Online content API provides access to articles from the ZEIT archive dating back to 1946 and from ZEIT ONLINE.\n|-\n| [[Dow Jones and Company]] || [http://new.dowjones.com/products/factiva/ Dow Jones Factiva] \n|| Enterprise Integration API  || \" Share content via enterprise integration API and embeddable widgets while honoring copyright holders.\"\n\n|-\n| [[ESPN]] || [http://developer.espn.com/docs/ ESPN API] NOTE: No new authorized access granted, as of Jan. 2015 [No longer available]  ||\n\n* Athlete API\n* Audio API\n* Draft API\n* Headlines API\n* Leaders API\n* Medals API\n* Now API\n* Photos API\n* Rankings API\n* Research Notes API\n* Scores & Schedules API\n* Standings API\n* Teams API\n* Video API \n || \n* Athlete API retrieves rosters of players for various sports, as well as biographical and statistical data for individual athletes.\n* Audio API retrieves ESPN on-demand audio content. This includes ESPN podcasts as well as clips from many live shows on ESPN Radio.\n* Draft API retrieves information about NBA and NFL draft picks.\n* Headlines API retrieves ESPN's various news stories.\n* Leaders API retrieves information on leading athletes in specific statistics categories.\n* Medals API provides medal and event result information from the Summer and Winter Olympic Games.\n* Now API provides a stream of the latest content published on ESPN.com, including headline news, stories, columns, blogs, videos, podcasts, game recaps, and more.\n* Photos API allows interaction with ESPN's photo content.\n* Rankings API provides rankings of teams and players for various sports, as well as recruiting rankings.\n* Research Notes API retrieves information from ESPN's vast knowledgebase of exclusive sports data.  \n* Scores & Schedules API provides game/match information, including start times, venue, competitors, score, and stats across every major sport.\n* Standings API retrieves latest standings for a particular sport by division, conference, or overall. \n* Teams API provides information on roster, stats, and more, for individual teams. \n* Video API allows interaction with ESPN's video-on-demand content, which includes hundreds of video clips each week.\n|-\n| [[Financial Times]] || [https://developer.ft.com/ FT for Developers] || \n*Headline API\n* Datamining API\n* Education API\n* Access API\n || \n* Headline API allows developers to integrate relevant FT content into the applications of their choice. \n* Datamining API allows developers to retrieve and host FT articles on their own servers to fully integrate the content into their own products. \n* Education API bring market context to learning resources, so students have a better understanding of the application of theory. \n* Access API displays full text FT articles co-mingled with content from other publishers.\n* Requires a subscription to the Financial Times.\n|-\n|  [[MSNBC]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150419012302/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/34622365 Using the msnbc.com APIs] || \n* Documents API\n* Entities API\n* Topics API\n || \n* Documents API represents articles, videos, images, slide shows, and other content available on msnbc.com. Documents API returns Documents related to a list of Entities (keywords), another Document, or a geographic location.\n* Entities API returns Entities associated with Documents and Topics. Entities are statistically-significant keywords associated Documents.\n* Topics pages are special msnbc.com pages that are created for entities that reach a specific threshold of \"importance\". The Topic API returns Topics pages related to Entities or Documents.\n\n|-\n| [[New York Times]] || [https://developer.nytimes.com/ The NYT External Developer APIs] || \n* Times Newswire API\n* Article Search API\n* Campaign Finance API\n* Community API\n* Congress API\n* Event Listings API\n* Geographic API\n* Movie Reviews API\n* Real Estate API\n* TimesTags API\n* Top Stories API\n || \n* Times Newswire API provides an up-to-the-minute stream of published items.\n* Article Search API retrieves headlines, abstracts and links to associated multimedia from 1851 to today.\n* Campaign Finance API retrieves presidential campaign contribution and expenditure data based on United States Federal Election Commission filings.\n* Community API retrieves comments by NYTimes.com users.\n* Congress API retrieves U.S. Congressional vote data, including information about specific House and Senate members.\n* Event Listings API retrieves information about handpicked events in New York City and the surrounding area.\n* Geographic API uses linked data to enhance location concepts used in The New York Times' controlled vocabulary.\n* Movie Reviews API retrieves links to reviews and NYT Critics' Picks, and search movie reviews by keyword.\n* Real Estate API retrieves aggregate data for real estate listings and sales in New York City.\n* TimesTags API retrieves standardized terms that match search queries, and filters by Times dictionaries.\n* Top Stories API provides lists of home page articles and associated images.\n\n|-\n| [[NPR]] || \n* [https://www.npr.org/api/index/ NPR Tech Center] \n* [http://dev.npr.org/ NPR One Developer Center]\n|| \n* Story API\n* Station Finder API\n*Transcript API\n|| \n* Story API provides audio from most NPR programs dating back to 1995.\n* Station Finder API used to identify local NPR member stations that carry NPR programming based on zip code, city/state, unique ID, call letters, longitude/latitude, and a few other parameters.\n* Transcript API provides access to full transcripts of stories airing on selected NPR programs. \n|-\n| [[PBS]] || [https://projects.pbs.org/confluence/display/coveapi/Welcome/ Documentation - COVE API] || Cove API || Cove API provides access to full PBS episodes, clips, and promotions.\n|-\n| [[Reuters]] || [https://agency.reuters.com/en/products-services/products/newswire-services.html]|| Robust Foundation API\n\n|| \nGlobal Newswires Services in 16 Languages. Rich with facts and context that speak to readers everywhere.\n\n|-\n| [[The Guardian]] || [http://open-platform.theguardian.com/ Guardian Open Platform] || Content API || Content API provides access to all the content the Guardian creates and the collections it has of that content (tags and sections). There are over one and a half million items available published as far back as 1999.\n|-\n| [[USA Today]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150301034023/http://developer.usatoday.com/ Developer's Network] || \n*Articles API\n* Best-Selling Books API\n* Book Reviews API\n* Breaking News API\n* Census API\n* Movie Reviews API\n* Snapshots API\n* Music Reviews API\n* Sports Salaries API\n || \n* Articles API retrieves USA TODAY stories going back to 2004.\n* Best-Selling Books API retrieves weekly list of the nation\u2019s top-selling books as compiled by USA TODAY.\n* Book Reviews API retrieves USA TODAY book reviews. \n* Breaking News API retrieves breaking news content.\n* Census API provides access to United States Census information.\n* Movie Reviews API retrieves USA TODAY movie review content.\n* Snapshots API retrieves easy-to-read statistical graphics that present information on various issues and trends in a visually appealing way.\n* Music Reviews API retrieves USA TODAY music review content.\n* Sports Salaries API provides information for the MLB, NFL, NBA and NHL, including player, position and team data and salary.\n\n|}\n\n== List of 3rd-party news APIs ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Company\n!Homepage\n!Sources\n!Pricing\n!Notes\n|-\n|Webhose.io \n|[https://webhose.io/topics/news-api/ Webhose News API]\n|Millions of news sites, blogs, message boards and review sites\n|$500 per 50,000 requests\n|Structured data in JSON/XML formats from over 75 million websites, and over 10 years of web archive. \n|-\n|Contify Newsfeed API\n|[https://www.contify.com/news-data-feeds-api/ Contify Newsfeed API]\n|>200,000 sources \n|$500 per 50,000 requests\n|Includes news and company websites, social media channels, review and discussion forums, job postings, regulatory portals, and more.\n|-\n|Currents API\n|[https://www.currentsapi.services/en Currents API]\n|>15,000 sources from >70 countries in 18 languages\n|$0.5 per 1000 requests\n|Include news categories, descriptions, and text\n|-\n|NewsAPI.org\n|[https://newsapi.org/ NewsApi.org]\n|>30,000, including ABC, BBC, Australian Financial Review and others\n|$1.8 per 1,000 requests\n|\n|-\n|Microsoft\n|[https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/services/cognitive-services/bing-news-search-api/ Bing News Search]\n|\n|$6 per 1,000 requests\n|Sources not specified\n|-\n|ContextualWeb News API\n|[https://contextualweb.io/news-api/ News API by ContextualWeb]\n|>100,000, including BBC, Guardian, Fox News, CNN and others\n|$0.5 per 1,000 requests\n|\n|-\n|Newslit\n|[https://rapidapi.com/newslit/api/newslit-news-search?gclid=Cj0KCQiAiNnuBRD3ARIsAM8KmltHKBR6m-mvaSIFuHYGlYJxHrRJkQXoGCr_3c8_aLwUDpRGK5CF5s8aAiiHEALw_wcB Newslit News Search]\n|>100,000\n|$8 per 1,000 requests\n|5,000 requests included in $40/month plan\n|-\n|zip.news API\n|[https://zip.news/us/prices.html News API by zip.news]\n|>5,000,000, group in NEWS, BLOG, TRAVEL, GOVERNMENT, TRAVEL\n|$70 per month\n| The result includes Sentiment NLP values + \"echo score\" + all NEWS articles are grouped in: Business, Politics, Culture, Local, Crime, Sport, Lifestyle, Gossip.\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using<ref></ref> tags, these references will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Journalism lists]]\n[[Category:Application programming interfaces]]\n[[Category:Electronic publishing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Orphan|date=December 2016}}\n\nSome [[online news media]] have created [[Application Programming Interface]]s (APIs) to enable computer applications to request stories and information about their stories ([[metadata]]) from them.\n\n== List of 1st-party news APIs ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! News organization || API home page || APIs || Note\n\n|-\n| [[American Broadcasting Company]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150909150340/http://developer.abc.com/docs/read/resources ABC Resources API]  || Resources API || Resources API retrieves content produced by ABC businesses, including national and local news, entertainment videos, and more.\n\n|-\n| [[Associated Press]] || [https://developer.ap.org/ AP Content API] \n|| \n* AP Content API\n* AP Breaking News API\n || \n* AP Content API allows the search and download of AP Images, one of the world\u2019s largest collections of historical and contemporary imagery.\n* AP Breaking News API retrieve a list of available breaking news categories and then requests content for a specific category.\n* Headlines and images only. Does not provide full text of articles.\n\n|-\n| [[BBC]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150810230518/https://developer.bbc.co.uk/content/bbc-platform-api BBC Platform API] [ Currently available only to BBC emplyees ] || Platform API || \n\"Platform API power all the BBC's product areas - iPlayer, News, Sport, Weather, Children's Knowledge and Learning - as well as many external and partner products such as Youview.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Billings|first1=Jon|title=Introducing Platform API|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/internet/entries/73c4f082-095f-3bf3-b4f0-53900e34a72b|accessdate=13 April 2015|date=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Bloomberg News]] || [http://www.bloomberglabs.com/api/ Bloomberg API] || Bloomberg API || Bloomberg API provides unrestricted access to raw data for customers for its financial market information. \n|-\n\n|-\n\n| [[CBS Sports]] || [http://developer.cbssports.com/documentation/ CBS Sports Development Center] [No longer available]||\n\n* Fantasy Live Scoring API\n* Rules API\n* Player Search API\n* Player Profile API\n* League Roster API\n* Schedule API\n* Salary and Wild Cards API\n* Playoff Settings API\n* Playoff Bracket API\n || \n* Fantasy Scoring API retrieves live scoring data for league.\n* Rules API retrieves rules for a fantasy league.\n* Player Search API retrieves a list of players.\n*Player Profile API retrieves a player's profile.\n* League Roster API retrieves roster for one team or all teams.\n* Schedule API retrieves schedule and match information.\n* Salary and Wild Cards API retrieve wildcard values for a set of players.\n* Playoff Settings API retrieves playoff settings for a league.\n* Playoff Bracket API retrieves a league\u2019s playoff bracket.\n\n|-\n| [[Die Zeit]] || [http://developer.zeit.de/index/ ZEIT ONLINE Content API] || Online Content API || Online content API provides access to articles from the ZEIT archive dating back to 1946 and from ZEIT ONLINE.\n|-\n| [[Dow Jones and Company]] || [http://new.dowjones.com/products/factiva/ Dow Jones Factiva] \n|| Enterprise Integration API  || \" Share content via enterprise integration API and embeddable widgets while honoring copyright holders.\"\n\n|-\n| [[ESPN]] || [http://developer.espn.com/docs/ ESPN API] NOTE: No new authorized access granted, as of Jan. 2015 [No longer available]  ||\n\n* Athlete API\n* Audio API\n* Draft API\n* Headlines API\n* Leaders API\n* Medals API\n* Now API\n* Photos API\n* Rankings API\n* Research Notes API\n* Scores & Schedules API\n* Standings API\n* Teams API\n* Video API \n || \n* Athlete API retrieves rosters of players for various sports, as well as biographical and statistical data for individual athletes.\n* Audio API retrieves ESPN on-demand audio content. This includes ESPN podcasts as well as clips from many live shows on ESPN Radio.\n* Draft API retrieves information about NBA and NFL draft picks.\n* Headlines API retrieves ESPN's various news stories.\n* Leaders API retrieves information on leading athletes in specific statistics categories.\n* Medals API provides medal and event result information from the Summer and Winter Olympic Games.\n* Now API provides a stream of the latest content published on ESPN.com, including headline news, stories, columns, blogs, videos, podcasts, game recaps, and more.\n* Photos API allows interaction with ESPN's photo content.\n* Rankings API provides rankings of teams and players for various sports, as well as recruiting rankings.\n* Research Notes API retrieves information from ESPN's vast knowledgebase of exclusive sports data.  \n* Scores & Schedules API provides game/match information, including start times, venue, competitors, score, and stats across every major sport.\n* Standings API retrieves latest standings for a particular sport by division, conference, or overall. \n* Teams API provides information on roster, stats, and more, for individual teams. \n* Video API allows interaction with ESPN's video-on-demand content, which includes hundreds of video clips each week.\n|-\n| [[Financial Times]] || [https://developer.ft.com/ FT for Developers] || \n*Headline API\n* Datamining API\n* Education API\n* Access API\n || \n* Headline API allows developers to integrate relevant FT content into the applications of their choice. \n* Datamining API allows developers to retrieve and host FT articles on their own servers to fully integrate the content into their own products. \n* Education API bring market context to learning resources, so students have a better understanding of the application of theory. \n* Access API displays full text FT articles co-mingled with content from other publishers.\n* Requires a subscription to the Financial Times.\n|-\n|  [[MSNBC]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150419012302/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/34622365 Using the msnbc.com APIs] || \n* Documents API\n* Entities API\n* Topics API\n || \n* Documents API represents articles, videos, images, slide shows, and other content available on msnbc.com. Documents API returns Documents related to a list of Entities (keywords), another Document, or a geographic location.\n* Entities API returns Entities associated with Documents and Topics. Entities are statistically-significant keywords associated Documents.\n* Topics pages are special msnbc.com pages that are created for entities that reach a specific threshold of \"importance\". The Topic API returns Topics pages related to Entities or Documents.\n\n|-\n| [[New York Times]] || [https://developer.nytimes.com/ The NYT External Developer APIs] || \n* Times Newswire API\n* Article Search API\n* Campaign Finance API\n* Community API\n* Congress API\n* Event Listings API\n* Geographic API\n* Movie Reviews API\n* Real Estate API\n* TimesTags API\n* Top Stories API\n || \n* Times Newswire API provides an up-to-the-minute stream of published items.\n* Article Search API retrieves headlines, abstracts and links to associated multimedia from 1851 to today.\n* Campaign Finance API retrieves presidential campaign contribution and expenditure data based on United States Federal Election Commission filings.\n* Community API retrieves comments by NYTimes.com users.\n* Congress API retrieves U.S. Congressional vote data, including information about specific House and Senate members.\n* Event Listings API retrieves information about handpicked events in New York City and the surrounding area.\n* Geographic API uses linked data to enhance location concepts used in The New York Times' controlled vocabulary.\n* Movie Reviews API retrieves links to reviews and NYT Critics' Picks, and search movie reviews by keyword.\n* Real Estate API retrieves aggregate data for real estate listings and sales in New York City.\n* TimesTags API retrieves standardized terms that match search queries, and filters by Times dictionaries.\n* Top Stories API provides lists of home page articles and associated images.\n\n|-\n| [[NPR]] || \n* [https://www.npr.org/api/index/ NPR Tech Center] \n* [http://dev.npr.org/ NPR One Developer Center]\n|| \n* Story API\n* Station Finder API\n*Transcript API\n|| \n* Story API provides audio from most NPR programs dating back to 1995.\n* Station Finder API used to identify local NPR member stations that carry NPR programming based on zip code, city/state, unique ID, call letters, longitude/latitude, and a few other parameters.\n* Transcript API provides access to full transcripts of stories airing on selected NPR programs. \n|-\n| [[PBS]] || [https://projects.pbs.org/confluence/display/coveapi/Welcome/ Documentation - COVE API] || Cove API || Cove API provides access to full PBS episodes, clips, and promotions.\n|-\n| [[Reuters]] || [https://agency.reuters.com/en/products-services/products/newswire-services.html]|| Robust Foundation API\n\n|| \nGlobal Newswires Services in 16 Languages. Rich with facts and context that speak to readers everywhere.\n\n|-\n| [[The Guardian]] || [http://open-platform.theguardian.com/ Guardian Open Platform] || Content API || Content API provides access to all the content the Guardian creates and the collections it has of that content (tags and sections). There are over one and a half million items available published as far back as 1999.\n|-\n| [[USA Today]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20150301034023/http://developer.usatoday.com/ Developer's Network] || \n*Articles API\n* Best-Selling Books API\n* Book Reviews API\n* Breaking News API\n* Census API\n* Movie Reviews API\n* Snapshots API\n* Music Reviews API\n* Sports Salaries API\n || \n* Articles API retrieves USA TODAY stories going back to 2004.\n* Best-Selling Books API retrieves weekly list of the nation\u2019s top-selling books as compiled by USA TODAY.\n* Book Reviews API retrieves USA TODAY book reviews. \n* Breaking News API retrieves breaking news content.\n* Census API provides access to United States Census information.\n* Movie Reviews API retrieves USA TODAY movie review content.\n* Snapshots API retrieves easy-to-read statistical graphics that present information on various issues and trends in a visually appealing way.\n* Music Reviews API retrieves USA TODAY music review content.\n* Sports Salaries API provides information for the MLB, NFL, NBA and NHL, including player, position and team data and salary.\n\n|}\n\n== List of 3rd-party news APIs ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Company\n!Homepage\n!Sources\n!Pricing\n!Notes\n|-\n|Webhose.io \n|[https://webhose.io/topics/news-api/ Webhose News API]\n|Millions of news sites, blogs, message boards and review sites\n|$500 per 50,000 requests\n|Structured data in JSON/XML formats from over 75 million websites, and over 10 years of web archive. \n|-\n|Contify Newsfeed API\n|[https://www.contify.com/news-data-feeds-api/ Contify Newsfeed API]\n|>200,000 sources \n|$500 per 50,000 requests\n|Includes news and company websites, social media channels, review and discussion forums, job postings, regulatory portals, and more.\n|-\n|Currents API\n|[https://www.currentsapi.services/en Currents API]\n|>15,000 sources from >70 countries in 18 languages\n|$0.5 per 1000 requests\n|Include news categories, descriptions, and text\n|-\n|NewsAPI.org\n|[https://newsapi.org/ NewsApi.org]\n|>30,000, including ABC, BBC, Australian Financial Review and others\n|$1.8 per 1,000 requests\n|\n|-\n|Microsoft\n|[https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/services/cognitive-services/bing-news-search-api/ Bing News Search]\n|\n|$6 per 1,000 requests\n|Sources not specified\n|-\n|ContextualWeb News API\n|[https://contextualweb.io/news-api/ News API by ContextualWeb]\n|>100,000, including BBC, Guardian, Fox News, CNN and others\n|$0.5 per 1,000 requests\n|\n|-\n|Newslit\n|[https://rapidapi.com/newslit/api/newslit-news-search?gclid=Cj0KCQiAiNnuBRD3ARIsAM8KmltHKBR6m-mvaSIFuHYGlYJxHrRJkQXoGCr_3c8_aLwUDpRGK5CF5s8aAiiHEALw_wcB Newslit News Search]\n|>100,000\n|$8 per 1,000 requests\n|5,000 requests included in $40/month plan\n|-\n|zip.news API\n|[https://zip.news/us/prices.html News API by zip.news]\n|>5,000,000, group in NEWS, BLOG, TRAVEL, GOVERMENT, TRAVEL\n|$70 per month\n| The result includes Sentiment NLP values + \"echo score\" + all NEWS articles are grouped in: Business, Politics, Culture, Local, Crime, Sport, Lifestyle, Gossip.\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using<ref></ref> tags, these references will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Journalism lists]]\n[[Category:Application programming interfaces]]\n[[Category:Electronic publishing]]\n", "name_user": "Allenthalben", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo: Government.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_news_media_APIs"}
{"title_page": "Trent Alexander-Arnold", "text_new": "{{short description|English association football player}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Trent Alexander-Arnold\n| image = Trent Alexander-Arnold 2018.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Alexander-Arnold with [[England national football team|England]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]]\n| fullname = Trent John Alexander-Arnold<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FWC/2018/pdf/FWC_2018_SQUADLISTS.PDF |title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia: List of players: England |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |page=10 |date=15 July 2018 |accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|10|7|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/trent-arnold/376875/ |title=T. Alexander-Arnold: Summary |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], England\n| height = {{convert|1.75|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/14732/Trent-Alexander-Arnold/overview |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Right-back]]\n| currentclub = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| clubnumber = 66\n| youthyears1 = 2004\u20132016\n| youthclubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C. Reserves and Academy|Liverpool]]\n| years1 = 2016\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps1 = 84<!-- LEAGUE ONLY -->\n| goals1 = 4<!-- LEAGUE ONLY -->\n| nationalyears1 = 2013\u20132014\n| nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2014\u20132015\n| nationalteam2 = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 11\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2016\n| nationalteam3 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2016\u20132017\n| nationalteam4 = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 10\n| nationalgoals4 = 7\n| nationalyears5 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 3\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| nationalyears6 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam6 = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 9\n| nationalgoals6 = 1\n| club-update = 14:24, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 19:06, 17 November 2019 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|ENG}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA Nations League]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals|2019 Portugal]]|}}\n}}\n'''Trent John Alexander-Arnold''' (born 7 October 1998) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right-back]] for {{English football updater|Liverpoo}} club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].\n\nBorn and raised in [[Liverpool]], Alexander-Arnold joined Liverpool's academy in 2004 and later captained the club at various youth levels. He made his senior debut in 2016, aged 18, and has since made over 100 club appearances. He won Liverpool's young [[Liverpool Player of the Season Awards|player of the season]] award in both 2017 and 2018, and in the latter year also became the youngest player from the club to start in a [[UEFA Champions League]] final. The following year, at the age of 20, he was nominated for the [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] award, named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] and Champions League Squad of the Season, and became the youngest-ever player to start in two consecutive Champions League finals, with Liverpool winning the [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final]].\n\nAlexander-Arnold has also represented England at various youth levels and made his senior debut in 2018. He has since featured at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], where he became only the fourth teenager to start a match for England in the tournament, and in the [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League]] where his nation ended third. Trent is also a cross spammer who likes pregnant women\n\n==Early life and career==\nAlexander-Arnold was born in [[West Derby]], [[Liverpool]], where he attended St Mary's Catholic Primary School.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/who-trent-alexander-arnold-you-9121409 |title=Who is Trent Alexander-Arnold? All you need to know about Liverpool youngster as he starts at Old Trafford |first=Marcus |last=Hogg |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=15 January 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpools-trent-alexander-arnold-happy-13962453 |title=Why Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold is happy, still dreaming and committed to being a defender |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |last=Kelly |first=Andy |date=28 November 2017 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> When he was six years old, local football club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] hosted a half-term  camp to which a number of pupils from his school were invited, and his was one of the names drawn from a hat to attend. There, he was spotted by academy coach Ian Barrigan who subsequently approached his parents to offer him the chance to join the club's academy. He began training two-to-three times a week, and in a variety of different positions, before later going on to captain the club at U16 and U18 level under coach [[Pepijn Lijnders]].<ref name=JPA>{{cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/1327966/2019/11/01/trent-alexander-arnold-exclusive/|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold exclusive: 15 moments that have shaped my career|publisher=The Athletic|last=Pearce|first=James|date=1 November 2019|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44081528 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold: Liverpool's local boy on family values & shining on world stage |website=BBC Sport |last=Roan |first=Dan |date=11 May 2018 |accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/team/academy/player/trent-alexander-arnold |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505234440/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/team/academy/player/trent-alexander-arnold |archivedate=5 May 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/trent-alexander-arnold-liverpool-exclusive-12993256 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold exclusive \u2013 My Liverpool dream came true but I'm only just getting started |first=James |last=Pearce |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=5 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-lijnders-trent-alexander-arnold-13024449 |title=Pep Lijnders Liverpool Q&A \u2013 on Trent Alexander-Arnold and the Reds' most important signing |first=James |last=Pearce |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=12 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> In the intervening period, at the age of 14, he left St. Mary's to enroll at [[Rainhill High School]], an educational institution which shares an affiliation with the football club.<ref name=RB>{{cite news|url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/theredbulletin/trent-alexander-arnold-game-changer|title=Meet Liverpool's Legend In The Making, Trent Alexander-Arnold|publisher=The Red Bulletin|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>  \n\nIt was also during his time in the academy that Alexander-Arnold converted from a [[Winger (sports)#Association Football|winger]] to a right-back as it was the position that offered him the clearest path to the first team and he excelled in his new role, even being singled out by former Liverpool captain [[Steven Gerrard]], who tipped him to have a bright future at the club in his autobiography.<ref name=JPA/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/724740/Liverpool-Steven-Gerrard-Jurgen-Klopp-EFL-Cup-Trent-Alexander-Arnold-Premier-League |title=Liverpool prodigy set to make debut against Tottenham after endorsement from Gerrard |first=Paul |last=Joyce |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |date=24 October 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> As a result of his rapid progression, and in the buildup to the [[2015\u201316 Liverpool F.C. season|2015\u201316 season]], Alexander-Arnold was selected in the first team squad by [[Manager (association football)|manager]] [[Brendan Rodgers]] for the team's final pre-season [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] where he marked his unofficial debut for the club in a 2\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/fixtures2015/first-team/swindon-v-liverpool-8476/match-centre |title=Match centre: Swindon v Liverpool |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=2 August 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-fc-teen-trent-alexander-9776590 |title=Liverpool FC teen Trent Alexander-Arnold: Who the Reds' latest young star is after debut against Swindon |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |last=Walsh |first=Kristian |date=3 August 2015 |accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Liverpool===\n====2016\u201317 season: Development and breakthrough====\nHaving previously taken part in Liverpool's pre-season tour of the United States, Alexander-Arnold made his professional debut on 25 October 2016, starting in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in the fourth round of the [[EFL Cup]]. He was [[Penalty card#Yellow card|booked]] in the first half for a foul on [[Ben Davies (footballer, born 1993)|Ben Davies]], which he later revealed could have ended in him being sent off, before being [[Substitute (association football)|substituted]] for first-choice right-back [[Nathaniel Clyne]] in the 68th minute.<ref name=JPA/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/liverpool/story/2960077/trent-alexander-arnold-hopeful-of-chance-in-liverpool-first-team |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold hopeful of chance in Liverpool first team |first=Glenn |last=Price |publisher=ESPN |date=28 September 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37686653 |title=Liverpool 2\u20131 Tottenham Hotspur |first=Luke |last=Reddy |website=BBC Sport |date=25 October 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> Despite the indiscretion, his performance was lauded by Gerrard who once again backed him \"to become a top professional\", and also earned a spot in the EFL Cup Team of the Round alongside teammate [[Daniel Sturridge]].<ref name = Uncle/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2016/october/team-of-the-round-a-stand-out-xi-from-efl-cup-round-four/ |title=Team of the Round: A stand-out XI from EFL Cup Round Four |publisher=English Football League |date=18 October 2016 |accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Trent Alexander Arnold 2016.jpg|thumb|Alexander-Arnold, pictured here in match against [[Arsenal F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Arsenal U18]] in 2016, captained the [[Liverpool F.C. Reserves and Academy|Liverpool U18]] side during his time in the academy.|alt=|left|170px]]\n\nAlexander-Arnold's breakthrough into the first team was rewarded with a new long-term contract in November and he started in Liverpool's next EFL Cup match later that month against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]. He was named [[Man of the Match]] for his performance after registering his first [[Assist (football)|assist]] for the club by setting up [[Forward (association football)|striker]] [[Divock Origi]] for the opening goal of a 2\u20130 win for Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/242420-trio-commit-long-term-futures-to-lfc-by-signing-new-deals |title=Trio commit long-term futures to LFC by signing new deals |first=James |last=Carroll |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=8 November 2016 |accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/premier-league/trent-alexanderarnold-when-he-was-liverpool-mascot-slaven-bilic-on-jose-mourinho-paper-talk/news-story/9bc46fdbec5542b456beb82531a9ed1d |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold when he was Liverpool mascot, Slaven Bilic on Jose Mourinho: Paper Talk |website=Fox Sports |date=30 November 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football365.com/news/16-conclusions-efl-cup-quarter-finals |title=16 Conclusions: EFL Cup quarter-finals |first=Daniel |last=Storey |website=Football365 |publisher=Ole Media Group |date=1 December 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> He then made his Premier League debut on 14 December, coming on as a late substitute in a 3\u20130 win over [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], and made his first league start in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 15 January 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/club/liverpool/364/blog/post/3019259/adam-lallana-man-of-the-match-performance-leads-liverpool-to-victory |title=Adam Lallana's man-of-the-match performance leads Liverpool to victory |first=Dave |last=Usher |publisher=ESPN |date=14 December 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/premier-league/zlatan-ibrahimovic-to-the-rescue-as-manchester-united-fight-back-to-claim-point-against-liverpool-35369322.html |title=Zlatan Ibrahimovic to the rescue as Manchester United fight back to claim point against Liverpool |first=Simon |last=Peach |newspaper=Irish Independent |location=Dublin |date=15 January 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> In May, having made 12 appearances across all competitions, he was named Liverpool's Young Player of the Season and was also nominated for the [[Professional Development League|Premier League 2]] Player of the Season award.<ref name=AK>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/no-trent-alexander-arnold-england-13273673 |title=No Trent Alexander-Arnold with England as Liverpool youngster prepares for huge season |first=Andy |last=Kelly |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=3 July 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=YPOTY>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/2017-liverpool-players-awards-live-13010663 |title=The 2017 Liverpool Players' Awards \u2013 Relive coverage of the end-of-season event at Anfield |first=Ian |last=Doyle |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=9 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpools-trent-alexander-arnold-ben-13065390 |title=Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold and Ben Woodburn up for award \u2013 but where's Harry Wilson? |first=Ian |last=Doyle |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=20 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/402106 |title=McBurnie named PL2 Player of the Season |publisher=Premier League |date=24 May 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season: First Champions League Final====\nIn the buildup to the [[2017\u201318 Liverpool F.C. season|2017\u201318 season]], regular right-back Clyne suffered a serious back injury which afforded Alexander-Arnold the opportunity to rotate with [[Joe Gomez (footballer)|Joe Gomez]] during the early stages of the campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/292305-trent-alexander-arnold-nathaniel-clyne |title=Trent: Competition has to be a part of LFC \u2013 fighting for your place is healthy |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Lynch |first=David |date=28 February 2018 |accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref> On 15 August 2017, he scored his first goal for the club when he struck home from a [[Direct free kick|free kick]] in a 2\u20131 first leg [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] play-off round win over [[Bundesliga]] team [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|Hoffenheim]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40924300 |title=1899 Hoffenheim 1\u20132 Liverpool |first=Phil |last=Dawkes |website=BBC Sport |date=15 August 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> In doing so, he became the third youngest player to score on his European debut for Liverpool, after [[Michael Owen]] and [[David Fairclough]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Stats/DebutGoalAges |title=Youngest debut goalscorers |website=LFCHistory.net |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> During the group stages of the competition, Alexander-Arnold scored again in a 7\u20130 [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] win over [[NK Maribor|Maribor]] on 17 October, a result which was the joint-largest ever away win in the competition, and largest away win by an English club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-za/news/liverpool-record-champions-league-firsts-with-seven-goal-mauling-/1lddar82iw4ma19djblaj0b0fg |title=Liverpool record Champions League firsts with seven goal Mauling |first=Chris |last=Burton |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=17 October 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> He then scored his first Premier League goal for Liverpool on [[Boxing Day]], netting in a 5\u20130 win over [[Swansea City F.C.|Swansea City]] at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/12/26/liverpool-vs-swansea-city-premier-league-live-score-updates/ |title=Liverpool 5 Swansea City 0: Roberto Firmino stars in five-goal rout of Swans |first1=Chris |last1=Bascombe |first2=JJ |last2=Bull |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=26 December 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Spartak Moscow- Liverpool.jpg|thumb|Alexander-Arnold (bottom, left-centre) lining-up for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] match against [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]] in 2017.|alt=|235x235px]]\n\nIn March the following year, Alexander-Arnold endured his most difficult spell with the club to date, after struggling against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] winger [[Wilfried Zaha]] and Manchester United's [[Marcus Rashford]] in successive weeks.<ref name=JPA/> Nonetheless, he retained his position in Liverpool's starting line-up to become the youngest English player to start in a Champions League quarter-final match and performed strongly in a 3\u20130 win over English rivals [[Manchester City]] in April. His performance saw him named Man of the Match and earned him praise from the media for his ability to nullify City winger [[Leroy San\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/liverpool-trent-alexanderarnold-champions-league-manchester-city-a8287331.html |title=Why Trent Alexander-Arnold's Liverpudlian roots mean so much in the era of football's global village |last=Liew |first=Jonathan |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=3 April 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2018/04/liverpool-3-0-man-city-player-ratings-2/ |title=Liverpool 3\u20130 Man City: Player Ratings |date=4 April 2018 |website=This Is Anfield |publisher=Soccer Publishing |accessdate=5 April 2018 |last=Twelves |first=Ben}}</ref> He impressed again in the reverse fixture as Liverpool eliminated City 5\u20131 on [[Two-legged tie|aggregate]] to advance to the semi-finals of the competition for the first time in 10 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/299076-trent-alexander-arnold-champions-league-as-roma |title='It means everything' \u2013 Trent on semi-final buzz |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Lynch |first=David |date=25 April 2018 |accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref> On 10 May, his domestic and European form was rewarded when he won the Liverpool Young Player of the Season award for the second season running.<ref name=YPOTY2>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/mohamed-salah-scoops-two-prizes-12514793 |title=Mohamed Salah scoops TWO prizes at Liverpool Players' Awards \u2013 before making frantic dash to London for FWA dinner |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |last=Prenderville |first=Liam |date=10 May 2018 |accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> Later that month, he became the youngest Liverpool player to start in a [[2018 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League final]] when he was named in the starting line-up against two-time reigning champions, [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]. Tasked with marking [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], he performed admirably though Liverpool ultimately succumbed to a 3\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.90min.in/posts/6071918-champions-league-final-player-ratings-from-real-madrid-s-3-1-win-over-liverpool |title=Champions League Final: Player Ratings From Real Madrid's 3\u20131 Win Over Liverpool |website=90min |publisher=HT Media |last=Chakraborty |first=Sushan |date=26 May 2018 |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/may/26/real-madrid-liverpool-champions-league-final-match-report |title=Real Madrid win Champions League as brilliant Bale sinks Liverpool |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |last=Taylor |first=Daniel |date=26 May 2018 |accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref> Following the conclusion of the season, in which he scored three goals in 33 appearances across all competitions, he was nominated for the [[Golden Boy (award)|Golden Boy]] award where he was later voted runner-up to [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] defender, [[Matthijs de Ligt]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/305647-trent-alexander-arnold-ben-woodburn-herbie-kane-golden-boy-award |title=Liverpool trio nominated for 2018 Golden Boy award |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Williams |first=Sam |date=1 July 2018 |accessdate=2 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttosport.com/news/calcio/golden-boy/2018/12/17-51186728/golden_boy_2018_il_trionfo_di_de_ligt/?a=2 |title=Golden Boy 2018, il trionfo di De Ligt|trans-title=Golden Boy 2018, the triumph of De Ligt |website=Tuttosport |date=17 December 2018 |accessdate=17 December 2018 |last=Franchi |first=Massimo |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season: Regular starter and Champions League title====\nDuring the early stages of the [[2018\u201319 Premier League|following season]], he made his 50th appearance for Liverpool when he started in a 2\u20131 victory over Tottenham; the same opposition against whom he had made his debut almost two years prior.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/316433-tottenham-liverpool-talking-points-firmino-wijnaldum |title=Spurs 1\u20132 Liverpool: Five talking points from Wembley |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Raynor |first=Dominic |date=15 September 2018 |accessdate=15 September 2018}}</ref> In October, he was one of 10 players nominated for the inaugural [[Kopa Trophy]], an award presented by ''[[France Football]]'' to the best young player under the age of 21, and ultimately ended sixth in the voting polls, having received votes from Owen, [[Denis Law]] and [[Pavel Nedv\u011bd]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/320342-alexander-arnold-kopa-trophy-shortlist |title=Trent named on Kopa Trophy shortlist |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Shaw |first=Chris |date=8 October 2018 |accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6239498-the-4-former-ballon-d-or-winners-who-voted-for-trent-alexander-arnold-in-kopa-trophy |title=The 4 Former Ballon d'Or Winners Who Voted for Trent Alexander-Arnold in Kopa Trophy |website=90min |publisher=HT Media |date=5 December 2018 |accessdate=6 December 2018 |last=Gott |first=Tom}}</ref> He continued to enhance his burgeoning reputation in the months thereafter and was consistently listed in reports by the [[International Centre for Sports Studies|CIES]] as the world's most valuable full-back from a transfer value perspective.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football-observatory.com/IMG/sites/b5wp/2018/239/en/ |title=Updated transfer valuations: Mbapp\u00e9 takes the lead |publisher=International Centre for Sports Studies (CIES) |first1=Raffaele |last1=Poli |first2=Roger |last2=Besson |first3=Lo\u00efc |last3=Ravenel |date=5 November 2018 |accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football-observatory.com/IMG/sites/b5wp/2018/245/en/ |title=Brand new list of top transfer values for big-5 league players |publisher=International Centre for Sports Studies (CIES) |first1=Raffaele |last1=Poli |first2=Roger |last2=Besson |first3=Lo\u00efc |last3=Ravenel |date=7 January 2019 |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref> Alexander-Arnold elevated his game further following the turn of the year and, on 27 February 2019, became the youngest player, aged 20 years and 143 days, to record three assists in a single Premier League match when he set up [[Sadio Man\u00e9]] twice and [[Virgil van Dijk]] once in a 5\u20130 win over [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref name=eply>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-bh/news/alexander-arnold-sets-premier-league-assist-record-as/4wshhjhdp0591h1napipkpbqf |title=Alexander-Arnold sets Premier League assist record as Liverpool crush Watford |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |last=Tolmich |first=Ryan |date=27 February 2019 |accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref> Less than two months later,  he became the fifth-youngest player to reach 50 Premier League appearances for the club, behind Owen, [[Raheem Sterling]], [[Robbie Fowler]] and Gerrard, when he started in a 3\u20131 win over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/344571-alexander-arnold-50-premier-league-appearances |title=Trent becomes LFC's fifth-youngest player to reach 50 PL appearances |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Price |first=Glenn |date=5 April 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/report?gameId=513517 |title=Liverpool go top with Salah winner in fightback against Southampton |publisher=ESPN |date=5 April 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref> His domestic form was rewarded later in April when he was nominated for the [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] award, although the award was won by Manchester City's Sterling, and he was later named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] alongside Liverpool teammates  van Dijk, Man\u00e9 and [[Andrew Robertson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/346676-trent-alexander-arnold-pfa-young-player-of-the-year-shortlist |title=Trent named on PFA Young Player of the Year shortlist |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Shaw |first=Chris |date=20 April 2019 |accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6355870-raheem-sterling-wins-pfa-young-player-of-the-year-award-after-magnificent-season-with-man-city |title=Raheem Sterling Wins PFA Young Player of the Year Award After Magnificent Season With Man City |website=90min |publisher=HT Media |last=Kennerley |first=Ross |date=28 April 2019 |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thepfa.com/news/2019/4/25/premier-league-team-of-the-year |title=PFA Premier League Team of the Year |publisher=Professional Footballers' Association |date=25 April 2019 |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:LFC Parade 2019 01 Trent Alexander-Arnold.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Alexander-Arnold during Liverpool's Champions League victory Parade.]]\n\nHis creative prowess came to the fore once again in May when, during a 3\u20132 win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], Alexander-Arnold equalled the Premier League record for the most assists by a defender in a season, with his two assists in the match raising his tally to 11. It also saw him and Robertson, who had 11 assists of his own, become the first set of defenders from the same team to record double figures for assists in the same season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/liverpools-flying-full-backs-alexander-arnold-and-robertson-make-/51evp7ilin7u1iwpzo39njjm3 |title=Liverpool's flying full-backs Alexander-Arnold and Robertson make Premier League assist history |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=4 May 2019 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> Three days later, with Liverpool trailing [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] 3\u20130 on aggregate after a first-leg defeat, he recorded two more assists, including an \"instinctive corner\" for Origi's winning goal, to help the club to a 4\u20133 aggregate victory and progress to a second consecutive Champions League final.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/liverpool/liverpool-fc-vs-fc-barcelona-trent-alexander-arnold-explains-match-winning-assist-a4136491.html |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold explains match-winning assist for Liverpool vs Barcelona |newspaper=Evening Standard |last=Ouzia |first=Malik |date=7 May 2019 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref> On the final day of the domestic season, Alexander-Arnold assisted Man\u00e9 in a 2\u20130 win over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] to break the Premier League record for the most assists by a defender in a domestic campaign, with 12, surpassing previous holders [[Andy Hinchcliffe]], [[Leighton Baines]] and Robertson.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-sa/news/alexander-arnold-breaks-premier-league-assist-record-for/19g1z8vb0ysak180ioqdnhukdn |title=Alexander-Arnold breaks Premier League assist record for defenders |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=12 May 2019 |accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.statsperform.com/resource/hes-running-the-game-from-right-back-sit-back-and-watch-a-trent-alexander-arnold-data-dive/|title=\"He's Running The Game From Right-Back: Sit Back And Watch A Trent Alexander-Arnold Data Dive|website=StatsPerform|publisher=Opta|last=Hopkins|first=Oliver|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> He then started in the [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League Final]], a 2\u20130 win over Tottenham, and became the youngest player to start in two successive finals in the competition, breaking the record set by [[A.C. Milan]]'s [[Christian Panucci]] in 1995.<ref name=ucly>{{cite news |url=http://www.sportbible.com/football/news-liverpools-alexander-arnold-makes-champions-league-final-history-20190601 |title=Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold Makes Champions League Final History |website=Sport Bible |last=Jabbar |first=Nasir |date=1 June 2019 |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> He was later named in the competition's Team of the Season and nominated for the [[UEFA Club Football Awards#Best Defender|Defender of the Season]] award.<ref name=cltots>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2607890.html |title=UEFA Champions League Squad of the Season |publisher=UEFA |date=2 June 2019 |accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2617489.html |title=Champions League positional awards: meet the nominees |publisher=UEFA |date=8 August 2019 |accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 season: Ballon d'Or Nomination====\n[[File:Liverpool vs. Chelsea, UEFA Super Cup 2019-08-14 53.jpg|thumb|Alexander-Arnold (far right) celebrates Liverpool's [[2019 UEFA Super Cup]] victory over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].]]\n\nAlexander-Arnold began the [[2019-20 Liverpool F.C. season|2019\u201320]] campaign with his position as Liverpool's right back cemented, and provided the assist for Origi's goal in the club's 4\u20131 opening game win over [[Norwich F.C.|Norwich]].<ref name=\"IrTimes1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/english-soccer/liverpool-hardly-break-sweat-to-leave-canaries-all-a-flutter-1.3982059 |title=Liverpool hardly break sweat to leave Canaries all a flutter |author=Hunter, Andy |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=9 August 2019}}</ref> In doing so, he became only the eighth player in the Premier League era to register an assist in five consecutive games, and the first to do so for Liverpool.<ref name=\"Squawka\">{{cite web |url=https://www.squawka.com/en/news/trent-alexander-arnold-matches-mesut-ozil-assist-liverpool |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold sets new Liverpool record by matching Mesut \u00d6zil feat |author=Smith, Chris |website=Squawka |date=9 August 2019}}</ref> He appeared in subsequent wins over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], as well as in Liverpool's triumph over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the [[2019 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]] where he scored a penalty in the shoot-out.<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/aug/14/liverpool-chelsea-uefa-super-cup-match-report |title=Liverpool sink Chelsea to lift Super Cup thanks to Adri\u00e1n shootout save |author=Taylor, Daniel |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 August 2019}}</ref> He then scored his first goal of the season during Liverpool's 2\u20131 league win over the Blues from a set-piece routine that was later nominated for the [[Premier League Goal of the Month]] award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1366583|title=Who of Willems, Tomori, Djenepo, Hendrick, Maddison, Cresswell, Alexander-Arnold or Kante produced the finest effort?|publisher=Premier League|date=4 October 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019}}</ref> The following month,  he was nominated for the [[2019 Ballon d'Or]] award, alongside six of his Liverpool teammates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/365217-salah-alexander-arnold-mane-alisson-wijnaldum-firmino-van-dijk-ballon-dor-shortlist|title=Seven Liverpool stars named on Ballon d'Or shortlist\n|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Shaw|first=Chris|date=21 October 2019|accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref> On 2 November, at the age of 21 years and 26 days, he became the fourth-youngest player to reach 100 appearances for Liverpool, behind Owen, Sterling and Fowler, and marked the occasion by assisting Man\u00e9 for the winning goal in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/370994-trent-alexander-arnold-100-games-landmark|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold becomes fourth-quickest to LFC landmark|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Carroll|first=James|date=2 November 2019|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref> Exactly one month later, he was voted as the 19th-best player in the world at the Ballon d'Or ceremony, and the highest-ranked full-back.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/376000-virgil-van-dijk-ballon-dor-result|title=Virgil van Dijk finishes runner-up for 2019 Ballon d'Or|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=2 December 2019|accessdate=3 December 2019|last=Shaw|first=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpool.com/liverpool-fc-news/features/ballon-dor-liverpool-award-list-17353826|title=The Liverpool achievement nobody noticed simply adds to what everybody already knew|website=Liverpool.com |publisher=Reach |last=Morgan|first=Dan|date=3 December 2019|accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref> He then made his [[FIFA Club World Cup]] debut during Liverpool's 2\u20131 semi-final win over reigning [[CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF]] champions [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]], and provided the match-winning assist for [[Roberto Firmino]] in stoppage time after coming on as a substitute for [[James Milner]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/12/18/football/1576698480_639915.html|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold tops 2019 Premier League assists chart|newspaper=Diario AS|last=Roche|first=Calum|date=18 December 2019|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> Three days later, he started and played the full 120 minutes as Liverpool were crowned champions for the first time in the club's history following a 1\u20130 win after [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra-time]] over [[Copa Libertadores]] champions [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/50869633|title=Flamengo 0\u20131: Roberto Firmino's extra-time strike delivers first Club World Cup for Liverpool|website=BBC Sport|date=21 December 2019|accessdate=22 December 2019|last=Poole|first=Harry}}</ref>\n\nUpon returning from Qatar, Liverpool recorded a 4\u20130 league win over second-placed [[Leicester City FC|Leicester City]] during a match in which Alexander-Arnold played a hand in all four goals by scoring one, assisting two, and winning a penalty which was converted by Milner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2019/dec/26/liverpool-right-back-playmaker-trent-alexander-arnold-leicester|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold is a unique playmaker in Liverpool's red machine|date=26 December 2019|accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref> He was later rewarded for his form with the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award, becoming the first full-back to claim the honour since [[Micah Richards]] in 2007.<ref name=POTM>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1563909 |title=Alexander-Arnold wins EA SPORTS Player of the Month |publisher=Premier League |date=10 January 2020 |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> Further recognition followed at the turn of the year, when he was named in the [[UEFA Team of the Year#Team of the Year 2019|2019 UEFA Team of the Year]].<ref name=UTOTY>{{cite news|url=https://toty.uefa.com/reveal|title=Revealed - Team of the Year 2019|date=15 January 2020|accessdate=15 January 2020|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> Alexander-Arnold then played a starring role in Liverpool's 2\u20131 win over Wolves as the club extended their unbeaten run in the league to 40 matches. During the encounter, he assisted captain [[Jordan Henderson]] for the opening goal and in the process became the first defender in the competition's history to reach double figures for assists in multiple campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2020/01/trent-delivers-a-premier-league-first-5-key-stats-from-wolves-1-2-liverpool/|title=Trent delivers a Premier League first \u2013 5 key stats from Wolves 1-2 Liverpool|website=This Is Anfield|last=Lusby|first=Jack|date=24 January 2019|accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> Towards the end of February, following a 3\u20132 win over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], he matched his league assist record from the campaign before and took his overall tally in the Premier League to 25, becoming the third-youngest player in the competition's history to reach a quarter-century of assists behind [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]] and [[Wayne Rooney]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/11942620/trent-alexander-arnolds-assist-record-for-liverpool-analysed|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold's assist record for Liverpool analysed|publisher=Sky Sports|date=24 February 2020|accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\n[[File:Trent Alexander-Arnold.jpg|thumb|upright|Alexander-Arnold represented [[England national football team|England]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.]]\n\nAlexander-Arnold has represented England at various youth levels and featured at the [[2015 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] in Chile.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/jul/06/trent-alexander-arnold-grassroots-hero-060718 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold says his grasroots days in Liverpool don't feel that long ago |publisher=The Football Association |date=6 July 2018 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> He also scored three goals for the [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]] team, including a brace against [[Croatia national under-19 football team|Croatia]] and another against [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain]] which secured England's qualification for the [[2017 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2016/nov/12/england-u19s-wales-report-121116 |title=A brace from Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold not enough to rescue a draw in Bangor |publisher=The Football Association |date=12 November 2016 |accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2017/mar/24/uefa-european-u19s-championship-elite-qualifying-round-england-3-0-spain-240317 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold at the Double as U19s qualify for Euros |publisher=The Football Association |date=24 March 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> He did not feature at the tournament itself as Liverpool reached an agreement with England to rest him ahead of the following season's league campaign, but the Three Lions went on to defeat [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal]] in the final to claim their first ever title in the competition.<ref name=AK/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jul/15/football-under-19-uefa-england-portugal-final |title=England win European Under-19 Championship as youth shines again |first=Nick |last=Ames |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |date=15 July 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> The month following the tournament, he was called up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] team for the first time for their [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualifiers]] against [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] and [[Latvia national under-21 football team|Latvia]], and made his debut in a 3\u20130 win over the latter. Two more appearances followed with the U21 side before he was promoted and solidified his status within the senior [[England national football team|England]] camp.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2017/08/trent-alexander-arnold-earns-1st-england-u21s-call-among-3-liverpool-players/ |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold earns 1st England U21s call-up among 3 Liverpool players |first=Jack |last=Lusby |website=This Is Anfield |publisher=Soccer Publishing |date=24 August 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/sep/05/england-under-21-latvia-european-championship-qualifier-match-report |title=England Under-21s serve up exhilarating fare in easy victory over Latvia |first=Ben |last=Fisher |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=5 September 2017 |accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nIn March 2018, while part of the U21 team, Alexander-Arnold was invited to train with the [[England national football team|senior national team]] for the first time ahead of their friendly matches against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/294961-trent-alexander-arnold-england |title=Trent trains with senior England squad |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Shaw |first=Chris |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref> He received his first call-up in May 2018 when he was named in [[Gareth Southgate]]'s squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44138600 |title=England World Cup squad: Trent Alexander-Arnold in 23-man squad |website=BBC Sport |date=16 May 2018 |accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> His debut followed on 7 June 2018 when he started in a 2\u20130 pre-tournament friendly win over [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] at [[Elland Road]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44246164 |title=England 2\u20130 Costa Rica |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=7 June 2018 |accessdate=7 June 2018}}</ref> Prior to the match, he was handed his match jersey by [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2018/06/07/prince-william-visits-england-squad-presents-trent-alexander/ |title=Prince William visits England squad and presents Trent Alexander-Arnold with his match shirt |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |last=Johnson |first=Jamie |date=7 June 2018 |accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Alexander-Arnold then made his debut in the competition on 28 June, starting in a 1\u20130 group-stage defeat to [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], after both sides had already confirmed their progression to the knockout stages. In doing so, he became only the fourth teenager to start a match for England at a World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/liverpool-teenager-alexander-arnold-joins-exclusive-england/va0gudxbok61m29jjimvulap |title=Liverpool teenager Alexander-Arnold joins exclusive England World Cup club |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=28 June 2018 |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> It remained, however, his only appearance as [[Kieran Trippier]] was preferred at right-back and featured throughout as England were defeated by [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in the semi-finals, and then again by Belgium in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Third place play-off|third place play-off]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2018/07/liverpool-trio-not-involved-as-england-lose-to-belgium-in-world-cup-third-place-playoff/ |title=Liverpool trio not involved as England lose to Belgium in World Cup third-place playoff |website=This Is Anfield |publisher=Soccer Publishing |last=Matchett |first=Karl |date=14 July 2018 |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 November 2018, during a friendly international, held in honour of Wayne Rooney, Alexander-Arnold scored his first senior international goal as England recorded a 3\u20130 win over the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref name=USA>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45174412 |title=England 3\u20130 USA |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=15 November 2018 |accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref> In doing so, and at the age of 20 years and 39 days, he became the youngest Liverpool player since Michael Owen in 1999 to score for the national team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/alexander-arnold-becomes-youngest-liverpool-player-in-20/2obs5nhfh92k1j3v8jugs8hd3 |title=Alexander-Arnold becomes youngest Liverpool player in 20 years to score for England |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=15 November 2018 |accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, he was part of the England squad which ended third at the inaugural [[UEFA Nations League]] and played the full match in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] win over [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in the third-place play-off.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/jun/09/england-v-switzerland-nations-league-third-place-play-off-live |title=England beat Switzerland on penalties to secure third place in Nations League third place play-off |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 June 2019 |accessdate=9 June 2019 |last=Smyth |first=Rob}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nAlexander-Arnold is widely regarded as one of the best attacking full-backs in world football as a result of his proficiency at occupying attacking spaces on the pitch and creating goalscoring opportunities for his teammates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/gallery/ranked-10-best-right-backs-world|title=Ranked! The 10 best right-backs in the world|website=FourFourTwo|publisher=Future|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2019/nov/10/liverpool-symmetrical-full-backs-world-leaders|title=Liverpool's symmetrical full-backs have turned them into world leaders|newspaper=The Guardian|last=Ronay|first=Barney|date=10 November 2019|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> During the early years of his career, he emerged as one of the Premier League's most creative players due to his role in assisting goals from early crosses and set-piece deliveries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/how-liverpools-trent-alexander-arnold-17446072|title=Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold has surpassed Man City's Kevin De Bruyne to cement midfield calls|newspaper=Liverpool Echo|last=Dunn|first=Connor|date=20 December 2019|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> He possesses an impressive passing range, which is attributed to his development as a [[midfielder]] during his time in Liverpool's youth academy, and has been one of Liverpool's designated set-piece specialists for deadball situations since the [[2017-18 Liverpool F.C. season|2017-18 campaign]].<ref name=sop1>{{cite new |url=http://africa.espn.com/soccer/blog/tactics-and-analysis/67/post/3710971/trent-alexander-arnold-is-already-a-world-class-full-back-but-he-might-not-be-there-for-long |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold is already a world-class full-back but he might not be there for long |publisher=ESPN |last=Cox |first=Michael |date=28 November 2018 |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=sop2>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45187181 |title=Liverpool: Why Trent Alexander-Arnold can back up the hype |website=BBC Sport |last=Sanders |first=Emma |date=22 August 2018 |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> His set-piece routine, which involves three parallel steps backwards and one to the right, has been likened to that of former [[rugby union]] [[fly-half]] [[Jonny Wilkinson]].<ref name=sop3>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/trent-alexander-arnold-my-dead-ball-routine-is-like-jonny-wilkinsons-6kqrjskzl|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold: 'My dead-ball routine is like Jonny Wilkinson's'|newspaper=The Times|date=21 December 2019|accessdate=26 December 2019|last=Robinson|first=Mark}}</ref> Under Liverpool manager J\u00fcrgen Klopp, whose tactical set-up placed creative responsibility on the shoulders of the club's full-backs, Alexander-Arnold was predominantly deployed down the right flank where his overlapping runs, switching of play, accuracy of crossing and work-rate in tracking back saw him become an important figure in the side's transitional, counter-attacking style of play.<ref name=sop3/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/18804/11374908/trent-alexander-arnold-on-the-rise-why-he-can-get-better-and-better |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold on the rise: Why he can get better and better |website=Sky Sports |last=Bate |first=Adam |date=16 May 2018 |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ccn.com/trent-alexander-arnold-is-reinventing-the-right-back-role-at-liverpool/|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold Is Reinventing the Right-Back Role at Liverpool|website=CCN.com|publisher=Hawkfish AS|last=Lea|first=Greg|date=27 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlexander-Arnold's craft and intelligence were singled out for particular praise by influential names such as [[Gary Lineker]] and F\u00e0bregas after his assist for the winning goal in the 2018\u201319 Champions League semi-final, a move in which he faked leaving the ball for a teammate before running back to deliver a corner while the opposition players had their backs turned.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2019/05/08/gary-lineker-and-cesc-fabregas-react-to-trent-alexander-arnolds/|title=Gary Lineker and Cesc Fabregas React to Trent Alexander-Arnold's Assist|website=hitc.com|date=8 May 2019|accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Melwood5.jpg|thumb|upright|Alexander-Arnold was born in [[West Derby]]; a short distance from [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool's]] training ground, [[Melwood]].|alt=|right]]\n\nAlexander-Arnold is the nephew of former [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] footballer, and former Manchester United club secretary, [[John Alexander (footballer, born 1955)|John Alexander]].<ref name = Uncle>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/liverpool/story/3008300/trent-alexander-arnold-breaks-through-at-liverpool-despite-man-united-family-ties |title=Alexander-Arnold breaks through at Liverpool despite Man United links |first=Mark |last=Ogden |publisher=ESPN |date=30 November 2016 |accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref> His maternal grandmother, Doreen Carling, was once also in a relationship with former United manager, [[Sir Alex Ferguson]], before moving to New York City where she later married. Alexander-Arnold was thus eligible to play for the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] prior to making his England debut.<ref name=TG>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/06/sports/soccer/liverpool-alexander-arnold.html |title=At Global Clubs, Local Players Serve as Connective Tissue |first=Rory |last=Smith |newspaper=The New York Times |date=6 February 2018 |accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> He has two brothers; Tyler, who is four years his senior and acts as his [[Sports agent|agent]], and Marcel, who is three years younger.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/liverpool-vs-real-madrid-champions-league-trent-alexanderarnold-journey-to-kiev-a8366301.html |title=The making of a man: Trent Alexander-Arnold's journey from Crosby to Kiev |newspaper=The Independent |last=Hughes |first=Simon |date=24 May 2018 |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/01/13/brothers-agents-marcus-rashford-trent-alexander-arnold-robbed/ |title=Brothers and agents of Marcus Rashford and Trent Alexander-Arnold robbed at gunpoint in Moss Side |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 January 2019 |accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOutside of football, Alexander-Arnold volunteers as an ambassador for the Liverpool-based charity ''An Hour for Others'', which seeks to provide underprivileged members of the community with anything from food hampers and toys to cooking and science lessons. He has supported the charity since being introduced to it by his mother in his mid-teens. During his time with Liverpool's academy, he and teammate Kris Owens pledged to support the initiative if either of them made it as professional footballers.<ref name=TG/> His philanthropy also expands beyond the charity and in March 2019, after signing a new boot sponsorship with [[Under Armour]] (the second most lucrative boot deal in England behind [[Harry Kane]]'s) he initiated plans to purchase plots in Liverpool and use the funds to construct new pitches for the community.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/trent-alexander-arnold-plans-pump-16008676 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold plans to pump millions into Liverpool economy after signing lucrative Under Armour deal |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |last=Gors |first=Paul |date=21 March 2019 |accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is also an avid [[chess]] player, having been introduced to the sport by his father as a youngster, and in 2018 he played an invitational match against world champion [[Magnus Carlsen]]. The match, which was played as part of a campaign to promote the sport, ended in defeat for Alexander-Arnold after seventeen moves; eight more than technology entrepreneur [[Bill Gates]] managed when he faced Carlsen a few months earlier.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/liverpool-fc-trent-alexander-arnold-england-magnus-carlsen-chess-world-champion-a8574621.html |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold is outsmarted by the world chess champion, but Liverpool's young buck remains wise beyond his years |newspaper=The Independent |last=Liew |first=Jonathan |date=8 October 2018 |accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref> Alexander-Arnold later explained how chess was more than just a pass time and had helped him in his football career by teaching him to think \"two or three moves ahead of the opposition\".<ref name=RB/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 11 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Europe\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!League!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Liverpool F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=sb1617>{{soccerbase season|86758|2016|name=Trent Alex-Arnold|accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|7||0||2||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||12||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Liverpool F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=sb1718>{{soccerbase season|86758|2017|name=Trent Alex-Arnold|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|19||1||2||0||0||0||12{{efn|name=UCL|Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||2||colspan=2|\u2014||33||3\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Liverpool F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=sb1819>{{soccerbase season|86758|2018|name=Trent Alex-Arnold|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|29||1||0||0||0||0||11{{efn|name=UCL}}||0||colspan=2|\u2014||40||1\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Liverpool F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=sb1920>{{soccerbase season|86758|2019|name=Trent Alex-Arnold|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|29||2||0||0||0||0||7{{efn|name=UCL}}||0||4{{efn|One appearance in [[FA Community Shield]], one appearance in [[UEFA Super Cup]], two appearances in [[FIFA Club World Cup]]|name=|group=}}||0||40||2\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!84||4||4||0||3||0||30||2||4||0||125||6\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|match played 17 November 2019}}<ref name=NFT>{{NFT player |id=71344 |name=Alexander-Arnold, Trent |accessdate=17 November 2019}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50160458 |title=Kosovo 0\u20134 England |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=17 November 2019 |accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[England national football team|England]]\n|2018||5||1\n|-\n|2019||4||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total||9||1\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n{{updated|match played 17 November 2019. England score listed first, score column indicates score after each Alexander-Arnold goal.}}<ref name=NFT/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ International goals by date, venue, cap, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!scope=col|No.\n!scope=col|Date\n!scope=col|Venue\n!scope=col|Cap\n!scope=col|Opponent\n!scope=col|Score\n!scope=col|Result\n!scope=col|Competition\n!scope=col class=unsortable|{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=row style=text-align:center|1\n|15 November 2018||[[Wembley Stadium]], London, England||align=center|5||{{fb|United States}}||align=center|2\u20130||align=center|3\u20130||[[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]||align=center|<ref name=USA/>\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:LFC Parade 2019 01.jpg|thumb|Alexander-Arnold (far right) was part of the Liverpool squad which won the [[UEFA Champions League]] trophy in 2019.]]\n'''Liverpool'''\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League|2018\u201319]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48368443 |title=Tottenham Hotspur 0\u20132 Liverpool |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2019 |accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref> runner-up: [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44258022 |title=Real Madrid 3\u20131 Liverpool |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=26 May 2018 |accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[2019 UEFA Super Cup|2019]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49332825 |title=Liverpool 2\u20132 Chelsea |first=Gary |last=Rose |website=BBC Sport |date=14 August 2019 |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n*[[FIFA Club World Cup]]: [[2019 FIFA Club World Cup|2019]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50869633 |title=Liverpool 1\u20130 Flamengo |first=Harry |last=Poole |website=BBC Sport |date=21 December 2019 |accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''England'''\n*[[UEFA Nations League]] third place: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48191915 |title=Switzerland 0\u20130 England |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=9 June 2019 |accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Liverpool Player of the Season Awards|Liverpool Young Player of the Season Award]]: [[2016\u201317 Liverpool F.C. season|2016\u201317]],<ref name=YPOTY/> [[2017\u201318 Liverpool F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=YPOTY2/>\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#Premier League 10|2018\u201319 Premier League]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48028713 |title=PFA Team of the Year: Paul Pogba, Raheem Sterling and Sadio Mane included in side |website=BBC Sport |date=25 April 2019 |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Golden Boy (award)|Golden Boy]] runner-up: 2018<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/330622-trent-alexander-arnold-golden-boy-2018 |title=Alexander-Arnold runner-up in Golden Boy 2018 award |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Williams |first=Sam |date=17 December 2018 |accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n*UEFA Champions League Squad of the Season: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League#Squad of the season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2607890.html |title=U