Guinness World Record]] for the most assists by a defender in a single season: 12 assists<ref>{{cite|title=Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold reflects on his record-breaking season and teammate rivalry|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/10/liverpools-trent-alexander-arnold-reflects-on-his-record-breaking-season-and-tea/|publisher=[[Guinness World Records]]|date=15 October 2019 |accessdate=12 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.liverpoolfc.com/team/first-team/player/trent-alexander-arnold Profile] at the Liverpool F.C. website\n*[http://www.thefa.com/england/mens-seniors/squad/trent-alexander-arnold Profile] at the Football Association website\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Liverpool F.C. squad}}\n{{England squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{2018\u201319 Premier League PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{2019 UEFA Team of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alexander-Arnold, Trent}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Black English sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English association football player}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Trent Alexander-Arnold\n| image = Trent Alexander-Arnold 2018.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Alexander-Arnold with [[England national football team|England]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]]\n| fullname = Trent John Alexander-Arnold<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FWC/2018/pdf/FWC_2018_SQUADLISTS.PDF |title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia: List of players: England |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |page=10 |date=15 July 2018 |accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|10|7|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/trent-arnold/376875/ |title=T. Alexander-Arnold: Summary |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], England\n| height = {{convert|1.75|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/14732/Trent-Alexander-Arnold/overview |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Right-back]]\n| currentclub = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| clubnumber = 66\n| youthyears1 = 2004\u20132016\n| youthclubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C. Reserves and Academy|Liverpool]]\n| years1 = 2016\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps1 = 84<!-- LEAGUE ONLY -->\n| goals1 = 4<!-- LEAGUE ONLY -->\n| nationalyears1 = 2013\u20132014\n| nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2014\u20132015\n| nationalteam2 = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 11\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2016\n| nationalteam3 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2016\u20132017\n| nationalteam4 = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 10\n| nationalgoals4 = 7\n| nationalyears5 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 3\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| nationalyears6 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam6 = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 9\n| nationalgoals6 = 1\n| club-update = 14:24, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 19:06, 17 November 2019 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|ENG}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA Nations League]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals|2019 Portugal]]|}}\n}}\n'''Trent John Alexander-Arnold''' (born 7 October 1998) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right-back]] for {{English football updater|Liverpoo}} club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].\n\nBorn and raised in [[Liverpool]], Alexander-Arnold joined Liverpool's academy in 2004 and later captained the club at various youth levels. He made his senior debut in 2016, aged 18, and has since made over 100 club appearances. He won Liverpool's young [[Liverpool Player of the Season Awards|player of the season]] award in both 2017 and 2018, and in the latter year also became the youngest player from the club to start in a [[UEFA Champions League]] final. The following year, at the age of 20, he was nominated for the [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] award, named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] and Champions League Squad of the Season, and became the youngest-ever player to start in two consecutive Champions League finals, with Liverpool winning the [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final]].\n\nAlexander-Arnold has also represented England at various youth levels and made his senior debut in 2018. He has since featured at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], where he became only the fourth teenager to start a match for England in the tournament, and in the [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League]] where his nation ended third.\n\n==Early life and career==\nAlexander-Arnold was born in [[West Derby]], [[Liverpool]], where he attended St Mary's Catholic Primary School.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/who-trent-alexander-arnold-you-9121409 |title=Who is Trent Alexander-Arnold? All you need to know about Liverpool youngster as he starts at Old Trafford |first=Marcus |last=Hogg |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=15 January 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpools-trent-alexander-arnold-happy-13962453 |title=Why Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold is happy, still dreaming and committed to being a defender |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |last=Kelly |first=Andy |date=28 November 2017 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> When he was six years old, local football club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] hosted a half-term  camp to which a number of pupils from his school were invited, and his was one of the names drawn from a hat to attend. There, he was spotted by academy coach Ian Barrigan who subsequently approached his parents to offer him the chance to join the club's academy. He began training two-to-three times a week, and in a variety of different positions, before later going on to captain the club at U16 and U18 level under coach [[Pepijn Lijnders]].<ref name=JPA>{{cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/1327966/2019/11/01/trent-alexander-arnold-exclusive/|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold exclusive: 15 moments that have shaped my career|publisher=The Athletic|last=Pearce|first=James|date=1 November 2019|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44081528 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold: Liverpool's local boy on family values & shining on world stage |website=BBC Sport |last=Roan |first=Dan |date=11 May 2018 |accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/team/academy/player/trent-alexander-arnold |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505234440/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/team/academy/player/trent-alexander-arnold |archivedate=5 May 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/trent-alexander-arnold-liverpool-exclusive-12993256 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold exclusive \u2013 My Liverpool dream came true but I'm only just getting started |first=James |last=Pearce |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=5 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-lijnders-trent-alexander-arnold-13024449 |title=Pep Lijnders Liverpool Q&A \u2013 on Trent Alexander-Arnold and the Reds' most important signing |first=James |last=Pearce |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=12 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> In the intervening period, at the age of 14, he left St. Mary's to enroll at [[Rainhill High School]], an educational institution which shares an affiliation with the football club.<ref name=RB>{{cite news|url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/theredbulletin/trent-alexander-arnold-game-changer|title=Meet Liverpool's Legend In The Making, Trent Alexander-Arnold|publisher=The Red Bulletin|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>  \n\nIt was also during his time in the academy that Alexander-Arnold converted from a [[Winger (sports)#Association Football|winger]] to a right-back as it was the position that offered him the clearest path to the first team and he excelled in his new role, even being singled out by former Liverpool captain [[Steven Gerrard]], who tipped him to have a bright future at the club in his autobiography.<ref name=JPA/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/724740/Liverpool-Steven-Gerrard-Jurgen-Klopp-EFL-Cup-Trent-Alexander-Arnold-Premier-League |title=Liverpool prodigy set to make debut against Tottenham after endorsement from Gerrard |first=Paul |last=Joyce |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |date=24 October 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> As a result of his rapid progression, and in the buildup to the [[2015\u201316 Liverpool F.C. season|2015\u201316 season]], Alexander-Arnold was selected in the first team squad by [[Manager (association football)|manager]] [[Brendan Rodgers]] for the team's final pre-season [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] where he marked his unofficial debut for the club in a 2\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/fixtures2015/first-team/swindon-v-liverpool-8476/match-centre |title=Match centre: Swindon v Liverpool |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=2 August 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-fc-teen-trent-alexander-9776590 |title=Liverpool FC teen Trent Alexander-Arnold: Who the Reds' latest young star is after debut against Swindon |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |last=Walsh |first=Kristian |date=3 August 2015 |accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Liverpool===\n====2016\u201317 season: Development and breakthrough====\nHaving previously taken part in Liverpool's pre-season tour of the United States, Alexander-Arnold made his professional debut on 25 October 2016, starting in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in the fourth round of the [[EFL Cup]]. He was [[Penalty card#Yellow card|booked]] in the first half for a foul on [[Ben Davies (footballer, born 1993)|Ben Davies]], which he later revealed could have ended in him being sent off, before being [[Substitute (association football)|substituted]] for first-choice right-back [[Nathaniel Clyne]] in the 68th minute.<ref name=JPA/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/liverpool/story/2960077/trent-alexander-arnold-hopeful-of-chance-in-liverpool-first-team |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold hopeful of chance in Liverpool first team |first=Glenn |last=Price |publisher=ESPN |date=28 September 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37686653 |title=Liverpool 2\u20131 Tottenham Hotspur |first=Luke |last=Reddy |website=BBC Sport |date=25 October 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> Despite the indiscretion, his performance was lauded by Gerrard who once again backed him \"to become a top professional\", and also earned a spot in the EFL Cup Team of the Round alongside teammate [[Daniel Sturridge]].<ref name = Uncle/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2016/october/team-of-the-round-a-stand-out-xi-from-efl-cup-round-four/ |title=Team of the Round: A stand-out XI from EFL Cup Round Four |publisher=English Football League |date=18 October 2016 |accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Trent Alexander Arnold 2016.jpg|thumb|Alexander-Arnold, pictured here in match against [[Arsenal F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Arsenal U18]] in 2016, captained the [[Liverpool F.C. Reserves and Academy|Liverpool U18]] side during his time in the academy.|alt=|left|170px]]\n\nAlexander-Arnold's breakthrough into the first team was rewarded with a new long-term contract in November and he started in Liverpool's next EFL Cup match later that month against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]. He was named [[Man of the Match]] for his performance after registering his first [[Assist (football)|assist]] for the club by setting up [[Forward (association football)|striker]] [[Divock Origi]] for the opening goal of a 2\u20130 win for Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/242420-trio-commit-long-term-futures-to-lfc-by-signing-new-deals |title=Trio commit long-term futures to LFC by signing new deals |first=James |last=Carroll |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=8 November 2016 |accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/premier-league/trent-alexanderarnold-when-he-was-liverpool-mascot-slaven-bilic-on-jose-mourinho-paper-talk/news-story/9bc46fdbec5542b456beb82531a9ed1d |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold when he was Liverpool mascot, Slaven Bilic on Jose Mourinho: Paper Talk |website=Fox Sports |date=30 November 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football365.com/news/16-conclusions-efl-cup-quarter-finals |title=16 Conclusions: EFL Cup quarter-finals |first=Daniel |last=Storey |website=Football365 |publisher=Ole Media Group |date=1 December 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> He then made his Premier League debut on 14 December, coming on as a late substitute in a 3\u20130 win over [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], and made his first league start in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 15 January 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/club/liverpool/364/blog/post/3019259/adam-lallana-man-of-the-match-performance-leads-liverpool-to-victory |title=Adam Lallana's man-of-the-match performance leads Liverpool to victory |first=Dave |last=Usher |publisher=ESPN |date=14 December 2016 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/premier-league/zlatan-ibrahimovic-to-the-rescue-as-manchester-united-fight-back-to-claim-point-against-liverpool-35369322.html |title=Zlatan Ibrahimovic to the rescue as Manchester United fight back to claim point against Liverpool |first=Simon |last=Peach |newspaper=Irish Independent |location=Dublin |date=15 January 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> In May, having made 12 appearances across all competitions, he was named Liverpool's Young Player of the Season and was also nominated for the [[Professional Development League|Premier League 2]] Player of the Season award.<ref name=AK>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/no-trent-alexander-arnold-england-13273673 |title=No Trent Alexander-Arnold with England as Liverpool youngster prepares for huge season |first=Andy |last=Kelly |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=3 July 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=YPOTY>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/2017-liverpool-players-awards-live-13010663 |title=The 2017 Liverpool Players' Awards \u2013 Relive coverage of the end-of-season event at Anfield |first=Ian |last=Doyle |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=9 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpools-trent-alexander-arnold-ben-13065390 |title=Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold and Ben Woodburn up for award \u2013 but where's Harry Wilson? |first=Ian |last=Doyle |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=20 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/402106 |title=McBurnie named PL2 Player of the Season |publisher=Premier League |date=24 May 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season: First Champions League Final====\nIn the buildup to the [[2017\u201318 Liverpool F.C. season|2017\u201318 season]], regular right-back Clyne suffered a serious back injury which afforded Alexander-Arnold the opportunity to rotate with [[Joe Gomez (footballer)|Joe Gomez]] during the early stages of the campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/292305-trent-alexander-arnold-nathaniel-clyne |title=Trent: Competition has to be a part of LFC \u2013 fighting for your place is healthy |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Lynch |first=David |date=28 February 2018 |accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref> On 15 August 2017, he scored his first goal for the club when he struck home from a [[Direct free kick|free kick]] in a 2\u20131 first leg [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] play-off round win over [[Bundesliga]] team [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|Hoffenheim]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40924300 |title=1899 Hoffenheim 1\u20132 Liverpool |first=Phil |last=Dawkes |website=BBC Sport |date=15 August 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> In doing so, he became the third youngest player to score on his European debut for Liverpool, after [[Michael Owen]] and [[David Fairclough]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Stats/DebutGoalAges |title=Youngest debut goalscorers |website=LFCHistory.net |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> During the group stages of the competition, Alexander-Arnold scored again in a 7\u20130 [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] win over [[NK Maribor|Maribor]] on 17 October, a result which was the joint-largest ever away win in the competition, and largest away win by an English club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-za/news/liverpool-record-champions-league-firsts-with-seven-goal-mauling-/1lddar82iw4ma19djblaj0b0fg |title=Liverpool record Champions League firsts with seven goal Mauling |first=Chris |last=Burton |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=17 October 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> He then scored his first Premier League goal for Liverpool on [[Boxing Day]], netting in a 5\u20130 win over [[Swansea City F.C.|Swansea City]] at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/12/26/liverpool-vs-swansea-city-premier-league-live-score-updates/ |title=Liverpool 5 Swansea City 0: Roberto Firmino stars in five-goal rout of Swans |first1=Chris |last1=Bascombe |first2=JJ |last2=Bull |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=26 December 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Spartak Moscow- Liverpool.jpg|thumb|Alexander-Arnold (bottom, left-centre) lining-up for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] match against [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]] in 2017.|alt=|235x235px]]\n\nIn March the following year, Alexander-Arnold endured his most difficult spell with the club to date, after struggling against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] winger [[Wilfried Zaha]] and Manchester United's [[Marcus Rashford]] in successive weeks.<ref name=JPA/> Nonetheless, he retained his position in Liverpool's starting line-up to become the youngest English player to start in a Champions League quarter-final match and performed strongly in a 3\u20130 win over English rivals [[Manchester City]] in April. His performance saw him named Man of the Match and earned him praise from the media for his ability to nullify City winger [[Leroy San\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/liverpool-trent-alexanderarnold-champions-league-manchester-city-a8287331.html |title=Why Trent Alexander-Arnold's Liverpudlian roots mean so much in the era of football's global village |last=Liew |first=Jonathan |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=3 April 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2018/04/liverpool-3-0-man-city-player-ratings-2/ |title=Liverpool 3\u20130 Man City: Player Ratings |date=4 April 2018 |website=This Is Anfield |publisher=Soccer Publishing |accessdate=5 April 2018 |last=Twelves |first=Ben}}</ref> He impressed again in the reverse fixture as Liverpool eliminated City 5\u20131 on [[Two-legged tie|aggregate]] to advance to the semi-finals of the competition for the first time in 10 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/299076-trent-alexander-arnold-champions-league-as-roma |title='It means everything' \u2013 Trent on semi-final buzz |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Lynch |first=David |date=25 April 2018 |accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref> On 10 May, his domestic and European form was rewarded when he won the Liverpool Young Player of the Season award for the second season running.<ref name=YPOTY2>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/mohamed-salah-scoops-two-prizes-12514793 |title=Mohamed Salah scoops TWO prizes at Liverpool Players' Awards \u2013 before making frantic dash to London for FWA dinner |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |last=Prenderville |first=Liam |date=10 May 2018 |accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> Later that month, he became the youngest Liverpool player to start in a [[2018 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League final]] when he was named in the starting line-up against two-time reigning champions, [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]. Tasked with marking [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], he performed admirably though Liverpool ultimately succumbed to a 3\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.90min.in/posts/6071918-champions-league-final-player-ratings-from-real-madrid-s-3-1-win-over-liverpool |title=Champions League Final: Player Ratings From Real Madrid's 3\u20131 Win Over Liverpool |website=90min |publisher=HT Media |last=Chakraborty |first=Sushan |date=26 May 2018 |accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/may/26/real-madrid-liverpool-champions-league-final-match-report |title=Real Madrid win Champions League as brilliant Bale sinks Liverpool |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |last=Taylor |first=Daniel |date=26 May 2018 |accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref> Following the conclusion of the season, in which he scored three goals in 33 appearances across all competitions, he was nominated for the [[Golden Boy (award)|Golden Boy]] award where he was later voted runner-up to [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] defender, [[Matthijs de Ligt]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/305647-trent-alexander-arnold-ben-woodburn-herbie-kane-golden-boy-award |title=Liverpool trio nominated for 2018 Golden Boy award |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Williams |first=Sam |date=1 July 2018 |accessdate=2 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttosport.com/news/calcio/golden-boy/2018/12/17-51186728/golden_boy_2018_il_trionfo_di_de_ligt/?a=2 |title=Golden Boy 2018, il trionfo di De Ligt|trans-title=Golden Boy 2018, the triumph of De Ligt |website=Tuttosport |date=17 December 2018 |accessdate=17 December 2018 |last=Franchi |first=Massimo |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season: Regular starter and Champions League title====\nDuring the early stages of the [[2018\u201319 Premier League|following season]], he made his 50th appearance for Liverpool when he started in a 2\u20131 victory over Tottenham; the same opposition against whom he had made his debut almost two years prior.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/316433-tottenham-liverpool-talking-points-firmino-wijnaldum |title=Spurs 1\u20132 Liverpool: Five talking points from Wembley |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Raynor |first=Dominic |date=15 September 2018 |accessdate=15 September 2018}}</ref> In October, he was one of 10 players nominated for the inaugural [[Kopa Trophy]], an award presented by ''[[France Football]]'' to the best young player under the age of 21, and ultimately ended sixth in the voting polls, having received votes from Owen, [[Denis Law]] and [[Pavel Nedv\u011bd]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/320342-alexander-arnold-kopa-trophy-shortlist |title=Trent named on Kopa Trophy shortlist |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Shaw |first=Chris |date=8 October 2018 |accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6239498-the-4-former-ballon-d-or-winners-who-voted-for-trent-alexander-arnold-in-kopa-trophy |title=The 4 Former Ballon d'Or Winners Who Voted for Trent Alexander-Arnold in Kopa Trophy |website=90min |publisher=HT Media |date=5 December 2018 |accessdate=6 December 2018 |last=Gott |first=Tom}}</ref> He continued to enhance his burgeoning reputation in the months thereafter and was consistently listed in reports by the [[International Centre for Sports Studies|CIES]] as the world's most valuable full-back from a transfer value perspective.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football-observatory.com/IMG/sites/b5wp/2018/239/en/ |title=Updated transfer valuations: Mbapp\u00e9 takes the lead |publisher=International Centre for Sports Studies (CIES) |first1=Raffaele |last1=Poli |first2=Roger |last2=Besson |first3=Lo\u00efc |last3=Ravenel |date=5 November 2018 |accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football-observatory.com/IMG/sites/b5wp/2018/245/en/ |title=Brand new list of top transfer values for big-5 league players |publisher=International Centre for Sports Studies (CIES) |first1=Raffaele |last1=Poli |first2=Roger |last2=Besson |first3=Lo\u00efc |last3=Ravenel |date=7 January 2019 |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref> Alexander-Arnold elevated his game further following the turn of the year and, on 27 February 2019, became the youngest player, aged 20 years and 143 days, to record three assists in a single Premier League match when he set up [[Sadio Man\u00e9]] twice and [[Virgil van Dijk]] once in a 5\u20130 win over [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref name=eply>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-bh/news/alexander-arnold-sets-premier-league-assist-record-as/4wshhjhdp0591h1napipkpbqf |title=Alexander-Arnold sets Premier League assist record as Liverpool crush Watford |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |last=Tolmich |first=Ryan |date=27 February 2019 |accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref> Less than two months later,  he became the fifth-youngest player to reach 50 Premier League appearances for the club, behind Owen, [[Raheem Sterling]], [[Robbie Fowler]] and Gerrard, when he started in a 3\u20131 win over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/344571-alexander-arnold-50-premier-league-appearances |title=Trent becomes LFC's fifth-youngest player to reach 50 PL appearances |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Price |first=Glenn |date=5 April 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/report?gameId=513517 |title=Liverpool go top with Salah winner in fightback against Southampton |publisher=ESPN |date=5 April 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref> His domestic form was rewarded later in April when he was nominated for the [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] award, although the award was won by Manchester City's Sterling, and he was later named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] alongside Liverpool teammates  van Dijk, Man\u00e9 and [[Andrew Robertson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/346676-trent-alexander-arnold-pfa-young-player-of-the-year-shortlist |title=Trent named on PFA Young Player of the Year shortlist |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Shaw |first=Chris |date=20 April 2019 |accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6355870-raheem-sterling-wins-pfa-young-player-of-the-year-award-after-magnificent-season-with-man-city |title=Raheem Sterling Wins PFA Young Player of the Year Award After Magnificent Season With Man City |website=90min |publisher=HT Media |last=Kennerley |first=Ross |date=28 April 2019 |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thepfa.com/news/2019/4/25/premier-league-team-of-the-year |title=PFA Premier League Team of the Year |publisher=Professional Footballers' Association |date=25 April 2019 |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:LFC Parade 2019 01 Trent Alexander-Arnold.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Alexander-Arnold during Liverpool's Champions League victory Parade.]]\n\nHis creative prowess came to the fore once again in May when, during a 3\u20132 win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], Alexander-Arnold equalled the Premier League record for the most assists by a defender in a season, with his two assists in the match raising his tally to 11. It also saw him and Robertson, who had 11 assists of his own, become the first set of defenders from the same team to record double figures for assists in the same season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/liverpools-flying-full-backs-alexander-arnold-and-robertson-make-/51evp7ilin7u1iwpzo39njjm3 |title=Liverpool's flying full-backs Alexander-Arnold and Robertson make Premier League assist history |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=4 May 2019 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> Three days later, with Liverpool trailing [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] 3\u20130 on aggregate after a first-leg defeat, he recorded two more assists, including an \"instinctive corner\" for Origi's winning goal, to help the club to a 4\u20133 aggregate victory and progress to a second consecutive Champions League final.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/liverpool/liverpool-fc-vs-fc-barcelona-trent-alexander-arnold-explains-match-winning-assist-a4136491.html |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold explains match-winning assist for Liverpool vs Barcelona |newspaper=Evening Standard |last=Ouzia |first=Malik |date=7 May 2019 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref> On the final day of the domestic season, Alexander-Arnold assisted Man\u00e9 in a 2\u20130 win over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] to break the Premier League record for the most assists by a defender in a domestic campaign, with 12, surpassing previous holders [[Andy Hinchcliffe]], [[Leighton Baines]] and Robertson.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-sa/news/alexander-arnold-breaks-premier-league-assist-record-for/19g1z8vb0ysak180ioqdnhukdn |title=Alexander-Arnold breaks Premier League assist record for defenders |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=12 May 2019 |accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.statsperform.com/resource/hes-running-the-game-from-right-back-sit-back-and-watch-a-trent-alexander-arnold-data-dive/|title=\"He's Running The Game From Right-Back: Sit Back And Watch A Trent Alexander-Arnold Data Dive|website=StatsPerform|publisher=Opta|last=Hopkins|first=Oliver|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> He then started in the [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League Final]], a 2\u20130 win over Tottenham, and became the youngest player to start in two successive finals in the competition, breaking the record set by [[A.C. Milan]]'s [[Christian Panucci]] in 1995.<ref name=ucly>{{cite news |url=http://www.sportbible.com/football/news-liverpools-alexander-arnold-makes-champions-league-final-history-20190601 |title=Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold Makes Champions League Final History |website=Sport Bible |last=Jabbar |first=Nasir |date=1 June 2019 |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> He was later named in the competition's Team of the Season and nominated for the [[UEFA Club Football Awards#Best Defender|Defender of the Season]] award.<ref name=cltots>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2607890.html |title=UEFA Champions League Squad of the Season |publisher=UEFA |date=2 June 2019 |accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2617489.html |title=Champions League positional awards: meet the nominees |publisher=UEFA |date=8 August 2019 |accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 season: Ballon d'Or Nomination====\n[[File:Liverpool vs. Chelsea, UEFA Super Cup 2019-08-14 53.jpg|thumb|Alexander-Arnold (far right) celebrates Liverpool's [[2019 UEFA Super Cup]] victory over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].]]\n\nAlexander-Arnold began the [[2019-20 Liverpool F.C. season|2019\u201320]] campaign with his position as Liverpool's right back cemented, and provided the assist for Origi's goal in the club's 4\u20131 opening game win over [[Norwich F.C.|Norwich]].<ref name=\"IrTimes1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/english-soccer/liverpool-hardly-break-sweat-to-leave-canaries-all-a-flutter-1.3982059 |title=Liverpool hardly break sweat to leave Canaries all a flutter |author=Hunter, Andy |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=9 August 2019}}</ref> In doing so, he became only the eighth player in the Premier League era to register an assist in five consecutive games, and the first to do so for Liverpool.<ref name=\"Squawka\">{{cite web |url=https://www.squawka.com/en/news/trent-alexander-arnold-matches-mesut-ozil-assist-liverpool |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold sets new Liverpool record by matching Mesut \u00d6zil feat |author=Smith, Chris |website=Squawka |date=9 August 2019}}</ref> He appeared in subsequent wins over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], as well as in Liverpool's triumph over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the [[2019 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]] where he scored a penalty in the shoot-out.<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/aug/14/liverpool-chelsea-uefa-super-cup-match-report |title=Liverpool sink Chelsea to lift Super Cup thanks to Adri\u00e1n shootout save |author=Taylor, Daniel |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 August 2019}}</ref> He then scored his first goal of the season during Liverpool's 2\u20131 league win over the Blues from a set-piece routine that was later nominated for the [[Premier League Goal of the Month]] award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1366583|title=Who of Willems, Tomori, Djenepo, Hendrick, Maddison, Cresswell, Alexander-Arnold or Kante produced the finest effort?|publisher=Premier League|date=4 October 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019}}</ref> The following month,  he was nominated for the [[2019 Ballon d'Or]] award, alongside six of his Liverpool teammates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/365217-salah-alexander-arnold-mane-alisson-wijnaldum-firmino-van-dijk-ballon-dor-shortlist|title=Seven Liverpool stars named on Ballon d'Or shortlist\n|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Shaw|first=Chris|date=21 October 2019|accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref> On 2 November, at the age of 21 years and 26 days, he became the fourth-youngest player to reach 100 appearances for Liverpool, behind Owen, Sterling and Fowler, and marked the occasion by assisting Man\u00e9 for the winning goal in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/370994-trent-alexander-arnold-100-games-landmark|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold becomes fourth-quickest to LFC landmark|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Carroll|first=James|date=2 November 2019|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref> Exactly one month later, he was voted as the 19th-best player in the world at the Ballon d'Or ceremony, and the highest-ranked full-back.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/376000-virgil-van-dijk-ballon-dor-result|title=Virgil van Dijk finishes runner-up for 2019 Ballon d'Or|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=2 December 2019|accessdate=3 December 2019|last=Shaw|first=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpool.com/liverpool-fc-news/features/ballon-dor-liverpool-award-list-17353826|title=The Liverpool achievement nobody noticed simply adds to what everybody already knew|website=Liverpool.com |publisher=Reach |last=Morgan|first=Dan|date=3 December 2019|accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref> He then made his [[FIFA Club World Cup]] debut during Liverpool's 2\u20131 semi-final win over reigning [[CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF]] champions [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]], and provided the match-winning assist for [[Roberto Firmino]] in stoppage time after coming on as a substitute for [[James Milner]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/12/18/football/1576698480_639915.html|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold tops 2019 Premier League assists chart|newspaper=Diario AS|last=Roche|first=Calum|date=18 December 2019|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> Three days later, he started and played the full 120 minutes as Liverpool were crowned champions for the first time in the club's history following a 1\u20130 win after [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra-time]] over [[Copa Libertadores]] champions [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/50869633|title=Flamengo 0\u20131: Roberto Firmino's extra-time strike delivers first Club World Cup for Liverpool|website=BBC Sport|date=21 December 2019|accessdate=22 December 2019|last=Poole|first=Harry}}</ref>\n\nUpon returning from Qatar, Liverpool recorded a 4\u20130 league win over second-placed [[Leicester City FC|Leicester City]] during a match in which Alexander-Arnold played a hand in all four goals by scoring one, assisting two, and winning a penalty which was converted by Milner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2019/dec/26/liverpool-right-back-playmaker-trent-alexander-arnold-leicester|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold is a unique playmaker in Liverpool's red machine|date=26 December 2019|accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref> He was later rewarded for his form with the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award, becoming the first full-back to claim the honour since [[Micah Richards]] in 2007.<ref name=POTM>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1563909 |title=Alexander-Arnold wins EA SPORTS Player of the Month |publisher=Premier League |date=10 January 2020 |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> Further recognition followed at the turn of the year, when he was named in the [[UEFA Team of the Year#Team of the Year 2019|2019 UEFA Team of the Year]].<ref name=UTOTY>{{cite news|url=https://toty.uefa.com/reveal|title=Revealed - Team of the Year 2019|date=15 January 2020|accessdate=15 January 2020|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> Alexander-Arnold then played a starring role in Liverpool's 2\u20131 win over Wolves as the club extended their unbeaten run in the league to 40 matches. During the encounter, he assisted captain [[Jordan Henderson]] for the opening goal and in the process became the first defender in the competition's history to reach double figures for assists in multiple campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2020/01/trent-delivers-a-premier-league-first-5-key-stats-from-wolves-1-2-liverpool/|title=Trent delivers a Premier League first \u2013 5 key stats from Wolves 1-2 Liverpool|website=This Is Anfield|last=Lusby|first=Jack|date=24 January 2019|accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> Towards the end of February, following a 3\u20132 win over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], he matched his league assist record from the campaign before and took his overall tally in the Premier League to 25, becoming the third-youngest player in the competition's history to reach a quarter-century of assists behind [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]] and [[Wayne Rooney]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/11942620/trent-alexander-arnolds-assist-record-for-liverpool-analysed|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold's assist record for Liverpool analysed|publisher=Sky Sports|date=24 February 2020|accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\n[[File:Trent Alexander-Arnold.jpg|thumb|upright|Alexander-Arnold represented [[England national football team|England]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.]]\n\nAlexander-Arnold has represented England at various youth levels and featured at the [[2015 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] in Chile.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/jul/06/trent-alexander-arnold-grassroots-hero-060718 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold says his grasroots days in Liverpool don't feel that long ago |publisher=The Football Association |date=6 July 2018 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> He also scored three goals for the [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]] team, including a brace against [[Croatia national under-19 football team|Croatia]] and another against [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain]] which secured England's qualification for the [[2017 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2016/nov/12/england-u19s-wales-report-121116 |title=A brace from Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold not enough to rescue a draw in Bangor |publisher=The Football Association |date=12 November 2016 |accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2017/mar/24/uefa-european-u19s-championship-elite-qualifying-round-england-3-0-spain-240317 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold at the Double as U19s qualify for Euros |publisher=The Football Association |date=24 March 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> He did not feature at the tournament itself as Liverpool reached an agreement with England to rest him ahead of the following season's league campaign, but the Three Lions went on to defeat [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal]] in the final to claim their first ever title in the competition.<ref name=AK/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jul/15/football-under-19-uefa-england-portugal-final |title=England win European Under-19 Championship as youth shines again |first=Nick |last=Ames |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |date=15 July 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> The month following the tournament, he was called up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] team for the first time for their [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualifiers]] against [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] and [[Latvia national under-21 football team|Latvia]], and made his debut in a 3\u20130 win over the latter. Two more appearances followed with the U21 side before he was promoted and solidified his status within the senior [[England national football team|England]] camp.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2017/08/trent-alexander-arnold-earns-1st-england-u21s-call-among-3-liverpool-players/ |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold earns 1st England U21s call-up among 3 Liverpool players |first=Jack |last=Lusby |website=This Is Anfield |publisher=Soccer Publishing |date=24 August 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/sep/05/england-under-21-latvia-european-championship-qualifier-match-report |title=England Under-21s serve up exhilarating fare in easy victory over Latvia |first=Ben |last=Fisher |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=5 September 2017 |accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nIn March 2018, while part of the U21 team, Alexander-Arnold was invited to train with the [[England national football team|senior national team]] for the first time ahead of their friendly matches against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/294961-trent-alexander-arnold-england |title=Trent trains with senior England squad |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Shaw |first=Chris |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref> He received his first call-up in May 2018 when he was named in [[Gareth Southgate]]'s squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44138600 |title=England World Cup squad: Trent Alexander-Arnold in 23-man squad |website=BBC Sport |date=16 May 2018 |accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> His debut followed on 7 June 2018 when he started in a 2\u20130 pre-tournament friendly win over [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] at [[Elland Road]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44246164 |title=England 2\u20130 Costa Rica |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=7 June 2018 |accessdate=7 June 2018}}</ref> Prior to the match, he was handed his match jersey by [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2018/06/07/prince-william-visits-england-squad-presents-trent-alexander/ |title=Prince William visits England squad and presents Trent Alexander-Arnold with his match shirt |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |last=Johnson |first=Jamie |date=7 June 2018 |accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Alexander-Arnold then made his debut in the competition on 28 June, starting in a 1\u20130 group-stage defeat to [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], after both sides had already confirmed their progression to the knockout stages. In doing so, he became only the fourth teenager to start a match for England at a World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/liverpool-teenager-alexander-arnold-joins-exclusive-england/va0gudxbok61m29jjimvulap |title=Liverpool teenager Alexander-Arnold joins exclusive England World Cup club |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=28 June 2018 |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> It remained, however, his only appearance as [[Kieran Trippier]] was preferred at right-back and featured throughout as England were defeated by [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in the semi-finals, and then again by Belgium in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Third place play-off|third place play-off]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2018/07/liverpool-trio-not-involved-as-england-lose-to-belgium-in-world-cup-third-place-playoff/ |title=Liverpool trio not involved as England lose to Belgium in World Cup third-place playoff |website=This Is Anfield |publisher=Soccer Publishing |last=Matchett |first=Karl |date=14 July 2018 |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 November 2018, during a friendly international, held in honour of Wayne Rooney, Alexander-Arnold scored his first senior international goal as England recorded a 3\u20130 win over the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref name=USA>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45174412 |title=England 3\u20130 USA |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=15 November 2018 |accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref> In doing so, and at the age of 20 years and 39 days, he became the youngest Liverpool player since Michael Owen in 1999 to score for the national team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/alexander-arnold-becomes-youngest-liverpool-player-in-20/2obs5nhfh92k1j3v8jugs8hd3 |title=Alexander-Arnold becomes youngest Liverpool player in 20 years to score for England |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=15 November 2018 |accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, he was part of the England squad which ended third at the inaugural [[UEFA Nations League]] and played the full match in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] win over [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in the third-place play-off.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/jun/09/england-v-switzerland-nations-league-third-place-play-off-live |title=England beat Switzerland on penalties to secure third place in Nations League third place play-off |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 June 2019 |accessdate=9 June 2019 |last=Smyth |first=Rob}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nAlexander-Arnold is widely regarded as one of the best attacking full-backs in world football as a result of his proficiency at occupying attacking spaces on the pitch and creating goalscoring opportunities for his teammates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/gallery/ranked-10-best-right-backs-world|title=Ranked! The 10 best right-backs in the world|website=FourFourTwo|publisher=Future|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2019/nov/10/liverpool-symmetrical-full-backs-world-leaders|title=Liverpool's symmetrical full-backs have turned them into world leaders|newspaper=The Guardian|last=Ronay|first=Barney|date=10 November 2019|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> During the early years of his career, he emerged as one of the Premier League's most creative players due to his role in assisting goals from early crosses and set-piece deliveries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/how-liverpools-trent-alexander-arnold-17446072|title=Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold has surpassed Man City's Kevin De Bruyne to cement midfield calls|newspaper=Liverpool Echo|last=Dunn|first=Connor|date=20 December 2019|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> He possesses an impressive passing range, which is attributed to his development as a [[midfielder]] during his time in Liverpool's youth academy, and has been one of Liverpool's designated set-piece specialists for deadball situations since the [[2017-18 Liverpool F.C. season|2017-18 campaign]].<ref name=sop1>{{cite new |url=http://africa.espn.com/soccer/blog/tactics-and-analysis/67/post/3710971/trent-alexander-arnold-is-already-a-world-class-full-back-but-he-might-not-be-there-for-long |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold is already a world-class full-back but he might not be there for long |publisher=ESPN |last=Cox |first=Michael |date=28 November 2018 |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=sop2>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45187181 |title=Liverpool: Why Trent Alexander-Arnold can back up the hype |website=BBC Sport |last=Sanders |first=Emma |date=22 August 2018 |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> His set-piece routine, which involves three parallel steps backwards and one to the right, has been likened to that of former [[rugby union]] [[fly-half]] [[Jonny Wilkinson]].<ref name=sop3>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/trent-alexander-arnold-my-dead-ball-routine-is-like-jonny-wilkinsons-6kqrjskzl|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold: 'My dead-ball routine is like Jonny Wilkinson's'|newspaper=The Times|date=21 December 2019|accessdate=26 December 2019|last=Robinson|first=Mark}}</ref> Under Liverpool manager J\u00fcrgen Klopp, whose tactical set-up placed creative responsibility on the shoulders of the club's full-backs, Alexander-Arnold was predominantly deployed down the right flank where his overlapping runs, switching of play, accuracy of crossing and work-rate in tracking back saw him become an important figure in the side's transitional, counter-attacking style of play.<ref name=sop3/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/18804/11374908/trent-alexander-arnold-on-the-rise-why-he-can-get-better-and-better |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold on the rise: Why he can get better and better |website=Sky Sports |last=Bate |first=Adam |date=16 May 2018 |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ccn.com/trent-alexander-arnold-is-reinventing-the-right-back-role-at-liverpool/|title=Trent Alexander-Arnold Is Reinventing the Right-Back Role at Liverpool|website=CCN.com|publisher=Hawkfish AS|last=Lea|first=Greg|date=27 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlexander-Arnold's craft and intelligence were singled out for particular praise by influential names such as [[Gary Lineker]] and F\u00e0bregas after his assist for the winning goal in the 2018\u201319 Champions League semi-final, a move in which he faked leaving the ball for a teammate before running back to deliver a corner while the opposition players had their backs turned.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2019/05/08/gary-lineker-and-cesc-fabregas-react-to-trent-alexander-arnolds/|title=Gary Lineker and Cesc Fabregas React to Trent Alexander-Arnold's Assist|website=hitc.com|date=8 May 2019|accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Melwood5.jpg|thumb|upright|Alexander-Arnold was born in [[West Derby]]; a short distance from [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool's]] training ground, [[Melwood]].|alt=|right]]\n\nAlexander-Arnold is the nephew of former [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] footballer, and former Manchester United club secretary, [[John Alexander (footballer, born 1955)|John Alexander]].<ref name = Uncle>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/liverpool/story/3008300/trent-alexander-arnold-breaks-through-at-liverpool-despite-man-united-family-ties |title=Alexander-Arnold breaks through at Liverpool despite Man United links |first=Mark |last=Ogden |publisher=ESPN |date=30 November 2016 |accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref> His maternal grandmother, Doreen Carling, was once also in a relationship with former United manager, [[Sir Alex Ferguson]], before moving to New York City where she later married. Alexander-Arnold was thus eligible to play for the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] prior to making his England debut.<ref name=TG>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/06/sports/soccer/liverpool-alexander-arnold.html |title=At Global Clubs, Local Players Serve as Connective Tissue |first=Rory |last=Smith |newspaper=The New York Times |date=6 February 2018 |accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> He has two brothers; Tyler, who is four years his senior and acts as his [[Sports agent|agent]], and Marcel, who is three years younger.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/liverpool-vs-real-madrid-champions-league-trent-alexanderarnold-journey-to-kiev-a8366301.html |title=The making of a man: Trent Alexander-Arnold's journey from Crosby to Kiev |newspaper=The Independent |last=Hughes |first=Simon |date=24 May 2018 |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/01/13/brothers-agents-marcus-rashford-trent-alexander-arnold-robbed/ |title=Brothers and agents of Marcus Rashford and Trent Alexander-Arnold robbed at gunpoint in Moss Side |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 January 2019 |accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOutside of football, Alexander-Arnold volunteers as an ambassador for the Liverpool-based charity ''An Hour for Others'', which seeks to provide underprivileged members of the community with anything from food hampers and toys to cooking and science lessons. He has supported the charity since being introduced to it by his mother in his mid-teens. During his time with Liverpool's academy, he and teammate Kris Owens pledged to support the initiative if either of them made it as professional footballers.<ref name=TG/> His philanthropy also expands beyond the charity and in March 2019, after signing a new boot sponsorship with [[Under Armour]] (the second most lucrative boot deal in England behind [[Harry Kane]]'s) he initiated plans to purchase plots in Liverpool and use the funds to construct new pitches for the community.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/trent-alexander-arnold-plans-pump-16008676 |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold plans to pump millions into Liverpool economy after signing lucrative Under Armour deal |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |last=Gors |first=Paul |date=21 March 2019 |accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is also an avid [[chess]] player, having been introduced to the sport by his father as a youngster, and in 2018 he played an invitational match against world champion [[Magnus Carlsen]]. The match, which was played as part of a campaign to promote the sport, ended in defeat for Alexander-Arnold after seventeen moves; eight more than technology entrepreneur [[Bill Gates]] managed when he faced Carlsen a few months earlier.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/liverpool-fc-trent-alexander-arnold-england-magnus-carlsen-chess-world-champion-a8574621.html |title=Trent Alexander-Arnold is outsmarted by the world chess champion, but Liverpool's young buck remains wise beyond his years |newspaper=The Independent |last=Liew |first=Jonathan |date=8 October 2018 |accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref> Alexander-Arnold later explained how chess was more than just a pass time and had helped him in his football career by teaching him to think \"two or three moves ahead of the opposition\".<ref name=RB/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 11 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2